WEBVTT

1
00:01:02.806 --> 00:01:04.797
[MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

2
00:01:21.525 --> 00:01:23.015
Will?

3
00:01:23.193 --> 00:01:24.387
WILL: What is it, Pa?

4
00:01:24.561 --> 00:01:26.290
Come out here.

5
00:01:30.701 --> 00:01:34.137
Listen. Your ears
are better than mine.


6
00:01:34.304 --> 00:01:36.864
Somebody's coming.

7
00:01:37.908 --> 00:01:39.102
I don't hear nothing.

8
00:01:39.276 --> 00:01:41.870
Turn off that whatchama-call-it.

9
00:01:42.045 --> 00:01:45.640
-The radio.
-I know what you call it. Turn it off.


10
00:01:45.816 --> 00:01:46.840
[TURNS RADIO OFF]

11
00:01:47.017 --> 00:01:50.475
First, I heard one of
them cars. Then it stopped.


12
00:01:50.654 --> 00:01:53.214
And now somebody's
coming down the hill.


13
00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:54.982
You hear?

14
00:01:55.792 --> 00:01:58.386
MAN: Y'all stay right here.
If I call, come a-running.


15
00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:06.663
Pa, that ain't no way to
welcome folks. Maybe it's kin.


16
00:02:06.837 --> 00:02:09.101
Kin don't come in no cars.

17
00:02:09.272 --> 00:02:12.435
See if you can wake
up that old hound dog.


18
00:02:13.844 --> 00:02:14.868
Hey, Blue?

19
00:02:15.045 --> 00:02:18.105
Come on, Blue. I got a
big old catfish head for you.


20
00:02:18.281 --> 00:02:20.476
Come on, Blue.

21
00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:23.619
Never seen such a crickety
dang pit in my whole life.


22
00:02:23.787 --> 00:02:25.755
Stuck up all over
here and everything.


23
00:02:25.922 --> 00:02:27.913
[CHICKENS CLUCKING]

24
00:02:30.093 --> 00:02:32.288
-Are you Will Stockdale?
-Howdy.


25
00:02:33.697 --> 00:02:36.029
Three dang times this
month, I've been out here--


26
00:02:36.199 --> 00:02:38.929
Don't you point your
finger in my boy's face.


27
00:02:39.102 --> 00:02:41.070
Are you threatening
me with a firearm?


28
00:02:41.238 --> 00:02:43.502
I'm a government
representative on business.


29
00:02:43.673 --> 00:02:46.938
Busting up here without
saying howdy or nothing.


30
00:02:47.110 --> 00:02:51.046
-What government?
-U.S. government. The draft board.


31
00:02:51.214 --> 00:02:53.910
This boy's been called for
the draft. He never reported.


32
00:02:54.084 --> 00:02:55.142
He's a draft dodger.

33
00:02:55.318 --> 00:02:59.846
Fold in that finger, sir. I'm
warning you, fold in that finger.


34
00:03:00.023 --> 00:03:02.685
He could go to jail for
that. He's in today's group.


35
00:03:02.859 --> 00:03:04.224
And this is your last chance.

36
00:03:04.394 --> 00:03:06.521
If you don't leave with
that group at 12 a.m...


37
00:03:06.696 --> 00:03:09.790
...you're gonna be in more
trouble than you ever did see.


38
00:03:09.966 --> 00:03:11.934
You already got one
offense against you.


39
00:03:12.102 --> 00:03:14.593
-Not answering my letters.
-I never got no letters.


40
00:03:14.771 --> 00:03:18.263
Don't tell me you can't read. You
could've got somebody to read them to you.


41
00:03:18.441 --> 00:03:20.875
-So that ain't no excuse.
-You mean to stand there...


42
00:03:21.044 --> 00:03:23.535
...and tell me to my
face my boy can't read?


43
00:03:23.713 --> 00:03:25.510
-Now, look--
-You think my boy...


44
00:03:25.682 --> 00:03:27.115
...who has gone to school...

45
00:03:27.284 --> 00:03:30.412
...and who has read more times
than you could shake a stick at...


46
00:03:30.587 --> 00:03:33.715
...couldn't read a puny little
old letter, if he wanted to?


47
00:03:33.890 --> 00:03:35.323
By dog, sir.

48
00:03:35.492 --> 00:03:37.016
I never got no letters.

49
00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:40.554
I don't think I can stand
to listen to any more of this.


50
00:03:40.897 --> 00:03:42.865
Get that book.

51
00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:46.628
No, sir, what you think
don't mean nothing to me...


52
00:03:46.803 --> 00:03:50.204
...but we are gonna settle this
here question right here and now...


53
00:03:50.373 --> 00:03:53.536
...and not have no
more foolishness about it.


54
00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:55.741
Read at him.

55
00:04:00.884 --> 00:04:04.479
"Once there was a
boy named Tony...


56
00:04:04.654 --> 00:04:06.986
...who wanted a pony.

57
00:04:07.157 --> 00:04:10.957
So he went to his mama and said:

58
00:04:11.127 --> 00:04:13.721
'May I have a pony? '

59
00:04:13.897 --> 00:04:16.593
And his Mama says:

60
00:04:17.868 --> 00:04:22.396
'No, Tony, you may
not have a pony.'"


61
00:04:22.939 --> 00:04:24.702
Go on.

62
00:04:28.378 --> 00:04:32.371
"So he went to
his papa and said:


63
00:04:32.549 --> 00:04:36.110
'Papa, may I have a pony? '

64
00:04:36.286 --> 00:04:38.311
And his papa says:

65
00:04:38.488 --> 00:04:42.822
'No, Tony, you may not have...

66
00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:45.751
...a pony.'"

67
00:04:46.429 --> 00:04:48.522
End of the book, he
gets the pony anyhow.


68
00:04:48.698 --> 00:04:52.395
Now that we have settled
if or not my boy can read--


69
00:04:52.569 --> 00:04:54.969
-Pa.
--you best be getting off my property...


70
00:04:55.138 --> 00:04:57.606
...and back in that car of
yours and out of range--


71
00:04:57.774 --> 00:05:00.242
-Pa, be Christian to him.
-Christian?


72
00:05:00.410 --> 00:05:02.310
You know what the
Lord would've done...


73
00:05:02.479 --> 00:05:05.642
...if a man come all hot and
stomping onto his property...


74
00:05:05.815 --> 00:05:07.612
...without saying
howdy or nothing?


75
00:05:07.817 --> 00:05:11.014
Scaring his chickens and
saying folks can't read?


76
00:05:12.122 --> 00:05:15.353
Sir, would it be all right if
me and Pa speak private-like?


77
00:05:15.525 --> 00:05:19.017
-Okay, but make it short.
-Thank you, sir.


78
00:05:19.195 --> 00:05:20.856
Come on, Pa.

79
00:05:21.164 --> 00:05:24.327
And don't try any funny business.
Because I ain't alone here.


80
00:05:26.336 --> 00:05:28.531
Set yourself, Pa.

81
00:05:31.274 --> 00:05:32.935
Now, listen, Pa.

82
00:05:33.109 --> 00:05:36.237
I don't think this here
draft's such a bad idea.


83
00:05:36.413 --> 00:05:38.540
I mean, I'd kind of like to go.

84
00:05:38.715 --> 00:05:43.175
There's a whole lot of fellas there and
they all march along right, snappy like.


85
00:05:43.353 --> 00:05:45.287
You listen to me, boy.

86
00:05:45.455 --> 00:05:48.686
Going in the draft don't
mean just going into town.


87
00:05:48.858 --> 00:05:52.225
It means Macon and
Atlanta and still further.


88
00:05:52.395 --> 00:05:57.492
I've been to Atlanta, you know
that. When I was no older than you.


89
00:05:57.667 --> 00:06:02.661
I told you how them folks laughed
at me and called me smart names.


90
00:06:02.839 --> 00:06:04.397
You don't want that, boy.

91
00:06:04.941 --> 00:06:08.843
-Pa, now ain't the same as it was then.
-Dogged if it ain't.


92
00:06:09.012 --> 00:06:13.472
But they want me. They even sent a
fella to come and fetch me, didn't they?


93
00:06:13.650 --> 00:06:15.117
And that ain't all.

94
00:06:15.285 --> 00:06:19.119
Last spring, I seen a sign on
the sidewalk down there in town.


95
00:06:19.289 --> 00:06:22.918
This great big old
picture of Uncle Sam.


96
00:06:23.093 --> 00:06:26.494
"And Uncle Sam wants
you," he's a-saying.


97
00:06:26.830 --> 00:06:31.392
Just like this fellow here, Pa, pointing
his finger right straight in my face.


98
00:06:31.901 --> 00:06:35.098
Don't you think a soldier fella
come up to me right then and there...


99
00:06:35.271 --> 00:06:38.502
...inviting me to come
along with all the other fellas?


100
00:06:39.275 --> 00:06:42.108
I told him how you
was ailing then...


101
00:06:42.278 --> 00:06:45.839
...and would he
kindly wait a while.


102
00:06:48.351 --> 00:06:50.876
You've been tearing up
them letters, ain't you, Pa?


103
00:06:53.957 --> 00:06:56.517
And you ain't ailing no more.

104
00:07:08.972 --> 00:07:13.568
-Hey, are you coming or do I have to--
-I'm just fixing to get me my shoes.


105
00:07:15.445 --> 00:07:17.538
You've got to know this:

106
00:07:17.714 --> 00:07:19.511
He's a good boy.

107
00:07:19.682 --> 00:07:22.242
It's my blame he didn't
come when he should've.


108
00:07:22.419 --> 00:07:24.887
I don't care who or why,
mister. We got him now.


109
00:07:25.055 --> 00:07:28.456
Remember, Pa? I got these
here for Aunt Tuzie's funeral.


110
00:07:28.625 --> 00:07:32.186
Ain't it nice I'm finally getting
a chance to wear them again?


111
00:07:33.596 --> 00:07:35.587
Appears they liked
to have shrunk a little.


112
00:07:35.765 --> 00:07:37.289
They'll put shoes
on you in Army.


113
00:07:37.467 --> 00:07:39.662
And ain't gonna wait
for you to put them on.


114
00:07:39.836 --> 00:07:44.535
Listen, draft man, you tell them
folks to be nice to my boy, you hear?


115
00:07:44.707 --> 00:07:47.107
-lf they ain't, I'll--
-I'm ready.


116
00:07:56.086 --> 00:07:59.078
Say goodbye to Blue for me
when he wakes up, will you?


117
00:07:59.255 --> 00:08:00.620
I will.

118
00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:05.723
-Write to me regular, you hear?
-Sure, Pa.


119
00:08:07.664 --> 00:08:09.188
Print big.

120
00:08:09.766 --> 00:08:11.529
I will.

121
00:08:13.269 --> 00:08:16.363
Remember, draft
man, what I said.


122
00:08:16.539 --> 00:08:19.474
-lf they ain't good to my boy....
-Yeah, I'll remember.


123
00:08:19.642 --> 00:08:21.576
Come on, boy, we gotta go.

124
00:08:21.744 --> 00:08:24.770
-Bye, Pa.
-Bye, Will.


