00:09:32.782 --> 00:09:35.615
Hey, look, they're
bringing a fella in bracelets.


145
00:09:40.390 --> 00:09:42.221
Finally latched onto
him, Mr. McKinney?


146
00:09:42.392 --> 00:09:44.155
-Did he give you any trouble?
-Trouble?


147
00:09:44.327 --> 00:09:46.557
Ain't no draft dodger
gonna give me any trouble.


148
00:09:46.729 --> 00:09:49.061
Had to borrow the
sheriff's handcuffs.


149
00:09:49.232 --> 00:09:51.291
That'll hold you till I
get you on that bus.


150
00:09:51.467 --> 00:09:54.334
-But, Mr. McKinney, I ain't dodging nothing.
-Shut up.


151
00:09:54.504 --> 00:09:56.131
Let me have it.

152
00:09:56.839 --> 00:10:00.400
Fill it out. Last name first, first name,
middle name last. Lean on the pump.


153
00:10:00.577 --> 00:10:04.570
-Last name first--
-First name, middle name last.


154
00:10:04.847 --> 00:10:06.144
Huh.

155
00:10:08.151 --> 00:10:12.315
-All right, any you boys had any ROTC?
-I did. Close to a year.


156
00:10:13.756 --> 00:10:16.122
-What's your name?
-Blanchard, Irving S.


157
00:10:16.292 --> 00:10:18.556
Irving? Okay, Irving.

158
00:10:18.728 --> 00:10:20.992
I'm setting you in
charge of this here group.


159
00:10:21.164 --> 00:10:23.223
When you get to your
classification center...


160
00:10:23.399 --> 00:10:25.833
...give these forms to the
sergeant of your barracks.


161
00:10:26.002 --> 00:10:29.665
-What about him?
-Keep them cuffs on him. Here are the keys.


162
00:10:30.373 --> 00:10:33.001
It took me three months to
flush him out of them hills...


163
00:10:33.176 --> 00:10:35.667
...so see that he
don't get away.


164
00:10:36.179 --> 00:10:38.477
Come on in my office,
Dave, I'll give you your money.


165
00:10:38.648 --> 00:10:39.808
Whew.

166
00:10:42.785 --> 00:10:46.744
You hear what he said, Plowboy? I
don't want any trouble, you understand?


167
00:10:46.923 --> 00:10:50.256
-Me, neither, Irving.
-My name's Blanchard to you.


168
00:10:50.426 --> 00:10:52.986
It's a real pleasure.

169
00:10:53.162 --> 00:10:55.221
You getting smart
with me, Plowboy?


170
00:10:55.398 --> 00:10:58.094
I don't wanna hear
one peep out of you.


171
00:10:58.268 --> 00:11:00.293
Not one peep.

172
00:11:06.609 --> 00:11:11.012
All right, I ain't had my morning coffee,
so I ain't gonna wait around to see you off.


173
00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:13.375
Now, Irving here's in charge.

174
00:11:13.549 --> 00:11:15.710
Callville is proud of
her sons in uniform...


175
00:11:15.885 --> 00:11:18.046
...so show them what
kind of men we raise here.


176
00:11:18.221 --> 00:11:21.657
And be good. And if you
can't be good, be careful.


177
00:11:21.824 --> 00:11:23.815
[LAUGHING]

178
00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:32.024
Rosabelle!

179
00:11:32.201 --> 00:11:33.225
Pa.

180
00:11:33.603 --> 00:11:35.537
Get on home!

181
00:11:35.705 --> 00:11:36.729
Yes, Pa.

182
00:11:36.906 --> 00:11:39.033
I told you to stay
home this time!


183
00:11:43.046 --> 00:11:44.604
Dang it.

184
00:11:45.882 --> 00:11:48.510
All right, all right, into the
bus when I call your name.


185
00:11:48.685 --> 00:11:50.915
-Deroy, Richard S.
-Here.


186
00:11:51.087 --> 00:11:52.816
-Farnum, Robert E.
-Here.


187
00:11:52.989 --> 00:11:54.718
-Hooper, Junior C.
-Here.


188
00:11:54.891 --> 00:11:58.019
-Lemon, Henry P.
-Here.


189
00:11:58.194 --> 00:12:01.721
-Stockdale, Will.
-Uh-- Here.


190
00:12:02.832 --> 00:12:04.891
I'll get around to you.

191
00:12:05.201 --> 00:12:07.931
-Swineburn, Armand A.
-Here.


192
00:12:08.204 --> 00:12:10.604
Whitledge, Benjamin B.

193
00:12:12.775 --> 00:12:15.073
Whitledge, Benjamin B.

194
00:12:15.244 --> 00:12:16.768
Here, here. Whitledge, here.

195
00:12:16.946 --> 00:12:19.039
-Benjamin B. Is Mr. McKinney here?
-Who?


196
00:12:19.215 --> 00:12:22.844
Mr. McKin-- Mr. McKinney, the man
on the draft board. I got a letter for him.


197
00:12:23.019 --> 00:12:24.919
Take it easy, sonny.
You just missed him.


198
00:12:25.088 --> 00:12:28.285
-Oh, I gotta find him. I got a letter for him.
-He left me in charge.


199
00:12:28.458 --> 00:12:32.861
Hey, give me that. That's a private letter.
It's official business for Mr. McKinney.


200
00:12:33.563 --> 00:12:35.428
Don't you understand English?

201
00:12:35.598 --> 00:12:37.691
I'm in charge.

202
00:12:39.102 --> 00:12:42.503
And here, fill out that form.

203
00:12:43.539 --> 00:12:46.906
-That's a private letter, you big--
-Hey.


204
00:12:47.176 --> 00:12:49.736
Don't get sore
at Irving, feller.


205
00:12:49.912 --> 00:12:51.880
He's had ROTC.

206
00:12:52.048 --> 00:12:55.074
That doesn't give him the
right to push me around.


207
00:12:55.685 --> 00:12:59.985
Hey, you put your last name
first, and then your first name.


208
00:13:00.156 --> 00:13:01.316
Like this.

209
00:13:01.491 --> 00:13:04.722
Stockdale, Will. 
Will Stockdale.

210
00:13:04.894 --> 00:13:07.454
Stockdale. Stockdale?

211
00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:09.791
All you need is one of each.

212
00:13:09.966 --> 00:13:11.558
Is that all?

213
00:13:11.734 --> 00:13:14.532
Wise guy. Oh.

214
00:13:16.973 --> 00:13:18.497
Much obliged.

215
00:13:18.674 --> 00:13:20.403
What's the matter with you?

216
00:13:20.576 --> 00:13:24.535
Oh, they think I'm a
draft dodger, but I ain't.


217
00:13:24.714 --> 00:13:28.309
Here, give me. You can't
write good with handcuffs.


218
00:13:28.484 --> 00:13:31.647
Thanks. Can't write much
good without them. Heh.


219
00:13:32.321 --> 00:13:34.482
-"Ever had measles? "
-No.


220
00:13:34.657 --> 00:13:36.181
-"The mumps? "
-No.


221
00:13:36.359 --> 00:13:38.088
-"Chickenpox? "
-No.


222
00:13:38.261 --> 00:13:44.325
-"Any other communicable diseases? "
-I reckon not.


223
00:13:44.634 --> 00:13:47.102
You figure they gonna
make me go back home?


224
00:13:47.270 --> 00:13:49.704
-"Ever break any bones? "
-Broke a leg bone once.


225
00:13:49.872 --> 00:13:52.136
-"Which leg? "
-The r-- No, it was the left.


226
00:13:52.308 --> 00:13:53.969
Yeah, left. Left.

227
00:13:54.143 --> 00:13:56.805
"Any member of your
family belong to groups...


228
00:13:56.979 --> 00:14:01.939
...planning to overthrow the
government by unconstitutional means? "


229
00:14:02.552 --> 00:14:05.316
No, we're pretty satisfied.

230
00:14:06.155 --> 00:14:08.316
-He still limps a mite.
-Who does?


231
00:14:08.491 --> 00:14:10.516
That fellow whose
leg bone I broke.


232
00:14:13.763 --> 00:14:15.788
He hit me first.

233
00:14:19.869 --> 00:14:21.530
You ever have ROTC?

234
00:14:22.772 --> 00:14:24.239
No.

235
00:14:24.407 --> 00:14:27.899
Hey, Irving had
it. Close to a year.


236
00:14:28.077 --> 00:14:31.706
He's so jumpy and all, I figure
he's still got a touch of it in him.


237
00:14:33.216 --> 00:14:35.548
-Listen, Stockdale, ROTC--
-Will's my name.


238
00:14:35.718 --> 00:14:38.516
-Will, listen, ROTC ain't--
-What was yours again?


239
00:14:38.688 --> 00:14:42.385
-Ben. Ben Whitledge. ROTC--
-Howdy.


240
00:14:43.326 --> 00:14:45.021
Hi.

241
00:14:45.995 --> 00:14:49.795
Look, Will, ROTC ain't
a disease. It's training.


242
00:14:49.966 --> 00:14:53.493
Reserve Officer
Training, uh, Corporation.


243
00:14:53.669 --> 00:14:57.002
-Heh. Is that the truth?
-Oh, sure. There's different kinds.


244
00:14:57.173 --> 00:15:01.837
There's cavalry ROTC,
artillery ROTC, infantry ROTC.


245
00:15:02.545 --> 00:15:06.914
-Infantry's the best.
-Yeah, that's what I always thought.


246
00:15:08.784 --> 00:15:13.312
-Ben, Irving ain't sick?
-No.


247
00:15:13.489 --> 00:15:15.354
And he don't rank
no higher than we do.


248
00:15:15.525 --> 00:15:19.518
Because ROTC don't mean
nothing unless you finish the course.


249
00:15:19.929 --> 00:15:21.453
IRVING: Hey, get this.

250
00:15:21.864 --> 00:15:23.923
"So I beg of you, Mr. McKinney.

251
00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:28.036
Please get my enclosed letter to the
commanding officer in the Air Force."


252
00:15:28.204 --> 00:15:30.365
Hey, you can't read that.

253
00:15:30.540 --> 00:15:33.441
"So that my son Ben
will be put in the infantry...


254
00:15:33.609 --> 00:15:36.077
...the same as his six
brothers before him."


255
00:15:36.245 --> 00:15:38.770
Give me that, you big--
Let go. Let-- Let go of me!


256
00:15:38.948 --> 00:15:43.112
"All his life, little Ben has been dreaming
of being a real infantry soldier...


257
00:15:43.286 --> 00:15:45.311
...like all the men
in our family."


258
00:15:45.774 --> 00:15:47.532
Little Ben wanna be
a great big soldier?


259
00:15:47.557 --> 00:15:48.581
[MEN LAUGHING]

260
00:15:49.025 --> 00:15:50.049
Irving?

261
00:15:51.761 --> 00:15:54.730
That letter belongs to
Ben. Now, you give it to him.


262
00:15:54.897 --> 00:15:58.697
I told you to keep your
mouth shut, Plowboy.


263
00:15:59.035 --> 00:16:04.337
"It'll break his poor heart if he's put in
the Air Force instead of the infantry...


264
00:16:04.507 --> 00:16:06.737
...so his brothers
will be proud of him."


265
00:16:06.909 --> 00:16:08.376
[MEN LAUGHING]

266
00:16:08.544 --> 00:16:12.810
Irving, you ain't sick like I
thought, so you give Ben his letter.


267
00:16:12.982 --> 00:16:14.916
Listen, Plowboy.

268
00:16:22.191 --> 00:16:23.317
Yeah, sure.

269
00:16:24.327 --> 00:16:26.591
I imagine it's time for
us to get going, ain't it?


270
00:16:26.762 --> 00:16:29.253
So I'd thank you if you'd
take these off, Irving.


271
00:16:29.432 --> 00:16:32.868
-They're beginning to chafe me a mite.
-Yeah.


272
00:16:33.202 --> 00:16:35.602
Yeah. Yeah, sure.

273
00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:41.069
All right, let's stop kidding around
here. Climb aboard there. Snappy now.


274
00:16:41.243 --> 00:16:43.609
Why, sure, Irving.

275
00:16:46.849 --> 00:16:48.441
All right, move
along. Move along.


276
00:16:48.618 --> 00:16:51.109
So long, boys. Don't
take any wooden nickels.


277
00:16:51.287 --> 00:16:53.118
[LAUGHS]

278
00:16:53.289 --> 00:16:57.589
I appreciate if you write me how
much it cost to get it fixed, Mr. McKinney.


279
00:16:57.760 --> 00:16:59.489
Bye.

280
00:17:14.243 --> 00:17:18.339
WILL: It sure was interesting when
we got to the classification center.


281
00:17:18.514 --> 00:17:21.312
They took us around from
one building to another.


282
00:17:21.484 --> 00:17:23.645
And they stuck
needles into our arms...


283
00:17:23.819 --> 00:17:26.788
...and whomped us on the
knees with a little rubber hammer...


284
00:17:26.956 --> 00:17:30.483
...and mashed down our
tongues with an ice cream stick.


285
00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:32.855
Then after a real nice supper...

286
00:17:33.029 --> 00:17:36.590
...I never had such a fill
of beans in my whole life...


287
00:17:36.766 --> 00:17:38.757
...we was all setting
around the barracks...


288
00:17:38.934 --> 00:17:41.459
...in our snappy new uniforms
learning how to salute...


289
00:17:41.637 --> 00:17:45.232
...everybody talking and joking
and feeling the back of their necks...


290
00:17:45.408 --> 00:17:47.933
...where they had these
horse clippers run over them...


291
00:17:48.110 --> 00:17:52.570
...when this nice fella,
this here sergeant, come in.


292
00:17:52.815 --> 00:17:53.839
[BLOWS WHISTLE]

293
00:17:54.350 --> 00:17:56.750
MAN 1: Hey. MAN 2:
Why, there's the sergeant.


294
00:17:56.919 --> 00:17:58.887
[MEN CHATTERING]

295
00:17:59.221 --> 00:18:02.190
Please, let's keep it quiet.

296
00:18:02.692 --> 00:18:04.956
On behalf of the president
of the United States...


297
00:18:05.127 --> 00:18:08.585
...Secretary of the Air Force, commanders
of this base and this squadron...


298
00:18:08.764 --> 00:18:11.927
...I wanna welcome you, gentlemen,
to the United States Air Force.


299
00:18:12.101 --> 00:18:16.663
This is a classification center where you will
undergo tests, both physical and mental...


300
00:18:16.839 --> 00:18:20.206
...designed to determine your
abilities so that you may be trained...


301
00:18:20.376 --> 00:18:23.812
...for the position from which
both you and the Air Force...


302
00:18:23.979 --> 00:18:26.447
...will derive the
greatest benefit.


303
00:18:27.216 --> 00:18:30.151
Tests are for you own good,
so do your best in every test.


304
00:18:30.319 --> 00:18:35.848
My name is King.
K-l-N-G, Sergeant King.


305
00:18:36.025 --> 00:18:39.859
I'm in charge of the barracks where
you will be billeted for two weeks.


306
00:18:40.029 --> 00:18:45.467
During that period, the barracks
will be kept spotlessly clean.


307
00:18:46.001 --> 00:18:50.438
This may be a stopping off place
for you, but for me, it is home.


308
00:18:50.873 --> 00:18:54.934
Before turning in tonight, every one of you
will write a letter to his nearest of kin...


309
00:18:55.111 --> 00:19:00.310
...informing them that you have arrived
safely and are in the best of health.


310
00:19:00.483 --> 00:19:04.214
If any problem should arise, feel
free to consult me about its solution.


311
00:19:04.386 --> 00:19:06.911
I am here to help you...

312
00:19:07.089 --> 00:19:11.253
...during these first difficult
days of military service.


313
00:19:14.463 --> 00:19:16.522
These are my quarters.

314
00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:24.298
Knock before entering.

315
00:19:24.874 --> 00:19:27.468
-That understood? 
MEN: Yes, sir.

316
00:19:27.643 --> 00:19:29.304
Roger.

317
00:19:29.578 --> 00:19:30.602
Wilco.

318
00:19:36.652 --> 00:19:38.176
[DOOR CLOSES]

319
00:19:39.989 --> 00:19:41.957
Seemed like a
right friendly fella.


320
00:19:42.892 --> 00:19:44.792
Be right back.

321
00:19:55.404 --> 00:19:56.701
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

322
00:19:56.872 --> 00:19:58.430
Come in.

323
00:20:01.644 --> 00:20:02.668
Private Blanchard...

324
00:20:02.845 --> 00:20:06.679
...delivering forms on 12
inductees from Callville as ordered.


325
00:20:06.849 --> 00:20:09.750
You keep standing like that,
you're gonna pull a muscle.


326
00:20:10.219 --> 00:20:12.380
Just put them down.

327
00:20:12.555 --> 00:20:15.456
Not on the bed, please.

328
00:20:23.966 --> 00:20:25.058
Anything else?

329
00:20:25.234 --> 00:20:28.897
Sergeant, I feel it's my duty to tell
you about one of the Callville inductees.


330
00:20:29.071 --> 00:20:32.438
Fella named Stockdale.
A draft dodger.


331
00:20:32.608 --> 00:20:34.542
He gave me a lot of trouble.

332
00:20:34.710 --> 00:20:36.735
Not on the bed, please.

333
00:20:42.051 --> 00:20:44.713
I was put in charge and
he gave me a lot of trouble.


334
00:20:44.887 --> 00:20:47.754
They brought him
to the bus in these.


335
00:20:50.025 --> 00:20:51.856
I'll make a note of it.

336
00:20:52.027 --> 00:20:54.518
I think he'll need some
disciplinary action.


337
00:20:54.697 --> 00:20:59.031
He already hit one of the
fellas with a gasoline pump.


338
00:20:59.201 --> 00:21:02.602
-In the barracks here?
-No, back at the bus station.


339
00:21:04.340 --> 00:21:06.240
I'll make a note of it.

340
00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:10.808
I thought he ought to be reported
to the squadron commander.


341
00:21:10.980 --> 00:21:13.244
-Oh, no.
-Well, I mean, I think it's my duty to--


342
00:21:13.415 --> 00:21:15.883
Any reporting done
around here, I do it.


343
00:21:16.285 --> 00:21:19.220
Sure you do. And this fella
Stockdale's a real troublemaker.


344
00:21:19.388 --> 00:21:22.380
Look, sonny, how long
have you been in the service?


345
00:21:22.558 --> 00:21:23.718
[MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

346
00:21:23.893 --> 00:21:27.454
About six hours, I guess.
I had ROTC though.


347
00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:30.190
I suppose they told
you it was all efficiency...


348
00:21:30.366 --> 00:21:32.891
...standing at attention,
running around.


349
00:21:33.068 --> 00:21:38.096
Well, I've been in for 18 years
and it ain't like you think it is at all.


350
00:21:38.274 --> 00:21:42.973
It's a quiet, peaceful life, if
you mind your own business.


351
00:21:43.145 --> 00:21:45.978
It's like there was a
big lake, nice and calm.


352
00:21:46.148 --> 00:21:49.811
I'm in a canoe, you're in another, the
captain's in a canoe and the colonel.


353
00:21:49.985 --> 00:21:53.352
You know what you do if you report
somebody or complain about somebody...


354
00:21:53.522 --> 00:21:55.285
...or request something?

355
00:21:56.158 --> 00:21:58.456
You make waves.

356
00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:04.963
Well, I thought the captain would
wanna know if he's got a troublemaker.


357
00:22:05.134 --> 00:22:07.659
I hate to pull rank on you,
but for your information...


358
00:22:07.836 --> 00:22:11.772
...you got the smallest canoe in
the whole lake. Good night, private.


359
00:22:14.977 --> 00:22:16.968
ANNOUNCER [OVER RADIO]:
And now our next request...


360
00:22:17.146 --> 00:22:20.912
...comes from Master
Sergeant Orville C. King...


361
00:22:21.083 --> 00:22:23.347
...at the Air Force
classification center.


362
00:22:23.519 --> 00:22:24.747
Here you are, Sergeant.

363
00:22:24.920 --> 00:22:26.911
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC
PLAYING OVER RADIO]


364
00:22:50.879 --> 00:22:55.145
Hey, Ben, do you put
a big "S" on "sergeant"?


365
00:22:55.317 --> 00:22:57.649
When you print it, it don't
make no difference, Will.


366
00:22:57.820 --> 00:23:00.516
Oh. Boy, Pa'll sure be happy...

367
00:23:00.689 --> 00:23:03.021
...about how Sergeant King
said it was really a home.


368
00:23:03.192 --> 00:23:04.716
[CHUCKLES]

369
00:23:07.363 --> 00:23:10.332
-No, come on, Ben, you take the bottom.
-No, Will.


370
00:23:10.499 --> 00:23:14.435
-But, honest, I like sleeping high.
-No, sir. You sat on the bottom bunk first.


371
00:23:14.603 --> 00:23:16.696
I didn't mean nothing
by it. Honest, I didn't.


372
00:23:16.872 --> 00:23:19.136
First come, first serve.
That's the military way.


373
00:23:19.308 --> 00:23:22.004
-No, now come on, Ben.
-I won't, I tell you!


374
00:23:22.177 --> 00:23:25.613
-Now, come on.
-Let that man alone, Stockdale.


375
00:23:25.781 --> 00:23:28.909
I'm beginning to think I never
should've taken the cuffs off of you.


376
00:23:29.418 --> 00:23:31.784
Well, Irving, I wasn't
doing nothing. I was just--


377
00:23:31.954 --> 00:23:35.219
Look, if you want some fighting,
you go after somebody your own size.


378
00:23:35.391 --> 00:23:38.053
-Not some little mouse.
-Watch your mouth!


379
00:23:38.227 --> 00:23:40.024
Why don't you mind
your own business?


380
00:23:40.195 --> 00:23:42.755
We're just stopping him
from wrestling you around.


381
00:23:42.931 --> 00:23:44.956
That's between him and
me, nobody asked you.


382
00:23:45.134 --> 00:23:46.226
Now, Ben, don't--

383
00:23:46.402 --> 00:23:50.839
-Only trying to do you a favor, junior.
-Who you calling Junior?


384
00:23:51.006 --> 00:23:52.701
Who asked you anything, anyhow?

385
00:23:52.875 --> 00:23:55.173
All right, if that's the
way you feel about it.


386
00:23:55.344 --> 00:23:59.610
You wanna be buddies with draft dodger,
be buddies with the draft dodger. Go ahead.


387
00:23:59.782 --> 00:24:03.013
-That's the way I feel about it.
-All right, before there's trouble...


388
00:24:03.185 --> 00:24:05.619
...you hit the sack.
Get to bed, both of you.


389
00:24:05.888 --> 00:24:07.515
I was just going to, Irving.

390
00:24:07.689 --> 00:24:10.624
BRONCO: Give him time,
Irving, beds is strange to Plowboy.


391
00:24:10.793 --> 00:24:12.658
He's used to
sleeping with the hogs.


392
00:24:12.828 --> 00:24:14.227
[LAUGHS]

393
00:24:14.396 --> 00:24:16.796
-What's the matter with you, anyhow?
-Me?


394
00:24:16.965 --> 00:24:19.957
Taking their insults and
heehawing like a dang donkey.


395
00:24:20.135 --> 00:24:22.160
They don't mean
nothing by it, Ben.


396
00:24:22.337 --> 00:24:25.272
Besides, I thought that one about
sleeping with the hogs is kind of funny.


397
00:24:25.441 --> 00:24:26.806
-Aww....
-Heh-heh.


398
00:24:26.975 --> 00:24:29.910
Well, see, I figure if we
just laugh with them...


399
00:24:30.079 --> 00:24:33.947
...why, pretty soon they'll get tired of
carrying on, there won't be no ruckus.


400
00:24:34.116 --> 00:24:37.085
You think a-laughing is
gonna stop these guys?


401
00:24:37.252 --> 00:24:39.914
A-licking is all
they understand.


402
00:24:41.023 --> 00:24:43.116
-You think so?
-I know so.


403
00:24:43.292 --> 00:24:46.420
And you behaving
like a dang donkey.


404
00:24:56.939 --> 00:24:59.271
MAN 1: Oh, what's he holding?

405
00:24:59.541 --> 00:25:01.441
MAN 2: You know...?
MAN 3: Oh, yeah.


406
00:25:01.610 --> 00:25:02.634
I'm through.

407
00:25:02.811 --> 00:25:04.278
-Yeah, I've had enough.
-Me too.


408
00:25:04.446 --> 00:25:06.038
Yeah.

409
00:25:08.317 --> 00:25:10.376
Lonesome for the hogs, Plowboy?

410
00:25:10.552 --> 00:25:12.782
Ain't used to living
indoors, are you, Plowboy?


411
00:25:12.955 --> 00:25:15.822
Look, Plowboy, you
want us to tuck you in bed?


412
00:25:15.991 --> 00:25:18.960
I bet your pa always
tucked you in nice and comfy.


413
00:25:19.128 --> 00:25:22.097
Wonder what kind
of hog his pa is.


414
00:25:22.264 --> 00:25:24.732
Chester White or Poland China?

415
00:25:24.900 --> 00:25:27.266
[MEN LAUGHING]

416
00:25:29.972 --> 00:25:31.837
I ain't gonna trouble
you fellas none...


417
00:25:32.007 --> 00:25:34.407
...because I know you
was all just put up to it.


418
00:25:34.576 --> 00:25:36.339
Excuse me.

419
00:25:38.814 --> 00:25:42.443
Irving, stand up and
take off them glasses.


420
00:25:42.618 --> 00:25:46.554
-Why?
-I aim to bust you up some.


421
00:25:47.723 --> 00:25:52.387
Look, Stockdale,
I'm not alone now.


422
00:25:52.561 --> 00:25:54.859
There's five of us here.

423
00:25:55.964 --> 00:25:58.489
MAN 1: Hit him! MAN

424
00:25:58.667 --> 00:25:59.691
MAN 3: Come on.

425
00:25:59.868 --> 00:26:02.860
MAN 4: Time out. MAN 5:
Come on, Plowboy, hit him.


426
00:26:03.739 --> 00:26:05.570
MAN 6: That's the end of it.

427
00:26:10.145 --> 00:26:12.545
MAN 7: Come on,
man. MAN 8: Come on.


428
00:26:12.915 --> 00:26:14.940
[DISCORDANT NOTE PLAYS]

429
00:26:15.117 --> 00:26:17.108
[MEN YELLING]

430
00:26:23.859 --> 00:26:25.588
Knock it off. Knock it off.

431
00:26:26.028 --> 00:26:28.292
Knock it off!

432
00:26:28.463 --> 00:26:29.862
[YELLING STOPS ABRUPTLY]

433
00:26:32.067 --> 00:26:36.470
Aren't you gentlemen starting in
a bit early to tip over my canoe?


434
00:26:36.638 --> 00:26:39.607
Sergeant, let me try to explain.

435
00:26:39.775 --> 00:26:41.538
Shut up.

436
00:26:42.010 --> 00:26:44.877
No, I am not in the
mood for explanations.


437
00:26:45.047 --> 00:26:46.947
I am quite tired.

438
00:26:47.115 --> 00:26:48.639
You understand?

439
00:26:48.817 --> 00:26:51.445
And I want no more noise.

440
00:26:51.620 --> 00:26:53.485
You understand, gentlemen?

441
00:26:56.024 --> 00:27:00.120
I will be more than willing to
listen to explanations in the morning.


442
00:27:00.862 --> 00:27:03.797
And as morning likes to come
a little early in the service...


443
00:27:03.966 --> 00:27:06.093
...we'll help it along.

444
00:27:06.268 --> 00:27:08.964
We won't wait for taps.

445
00:27:09.905 --> 00:27:11.770
Get to your bunks.

446
00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:15.171
On the double! Ooh!

447
00:27:19.715 --> 00:27:21.683
He seems a mite upset.

448
00:27:21.850 --> 00:27:23.841
Oh, Will.

449
00:27:26.188 --> 00:27:29.783
We better put Irving in his bed. He
won't wanna disobey the sergeant.


450
00:27:31.927 --> 00:27:33.918
You get his feet.

451
00:27:43.639 --> 00:27:45.231
Let him alone, please, Will.

452
00:27:45.407 --> 00:27:47.967
He'll wake up and
cause some more trouble.


453
00:27:48.143 --> 00:27:50.304
Yeah, I reckon he might.

454
00:27:50.479 --> 00:27:55.815
-Pretty good fight, though, wasn't it?
-Dog it, Will, this'll mess up everything.


455
00:27:55.984 --> 00:27:58.646
-What will, Ben?
-Fighting in the barracks.


456
00:27:58.820 --> 00:28:00.947
But you said licking
was all they'd understand.


457
00:28:01.123 --> 00:28:02.488
Not in the barracks.

458
00:28:02.658 --> 00:28:06.219
One of them's bound to snitch
tomorrow that we started a fight.


459
00:28:06.628 --> 00:28:09.654
Dog it, I'll never get
in the infantry now.


460
00:28:09.831 --> 00:28:13.323
If we kept our mouths shut and didn't
do nothing, we might get transferred.


461
00:28:13.502 --> 00:28:14.867
Both of us?

462
00:28:15.037 --> 00:28:17.267
But now, they're sure
to tell about the fight.


463
00:28:17.439 --> 00:28:18.906
No, they won't.

464
00:28:19.074 --> 00:28:22.737
If one of them says anything, I'll take
him out in the back and whomp him good.


465
00:28:22.911 --> 00:28:24.902
Now, there you go, Will.

466
00:28:25.080 --> 00:28:27.810
You think the infantry
wants men like that?


467
00:28:27.983 --> 00:28:30.884
No, they want men who can
take it and keep their mouths shut...


468
00:28:31.053 --> 00:28:32.987
...the way a man ought to do.

469
00:28:33.388 --> 00:28:35.151
Transfer?

470
00:28:35.590 --> 00:28:38.821
We'll be lucky if they don't
transfer us into the Navy.


471
00:28:38.994 --> 00:28:41.656
Walking around in them
little old white uniforms.


472
00:28:41.830 --> 00:28:44.594
Do you really want both
of us to transfer, Ben?


473
00:28:44.766 --> 00:28:48.759
Don't you understand, Will? It's
the infantry does the real fighting.


474
00:28:48.937 --> 00:28:51.030
All the rest is just helpers.

475
00:28:51.206 --> 00:28:53.674
Look at the War Between
the States. How about that?


476
00:28:53.842 --> 00:28:55.332
Yeah. How about that?

477
00:28:55.510 --> 00:28:57.535
See what I mean?

478
00:28:58.213 --> 00:29:00.443
Every man in my family's
been in the infantry...


479
00:29:00.615 --> 00:29:02.776
...clear back to
my great grandpa.


480
00:29:02.951 --> 00:29:04.248
You know what he done?

481
00:29:04.419 --> 00:29:06.785
Fought with Stonewall
Jackson at Chancellorsville.


482
00:29:06.955 --> 00:29:09.788
Licked him good too, I bet.

483
00:29:12.194 --> 00:29:14.389
By dog.

484
00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:22.568
First thing tomorrow, I'm gonna get
sergeant's permission to see the captain.


485
00:29:23.171 --> 00:29:26.436
I'll give him Ma's letter
and I'll.... And I'll....


486
00:29:28.076 --> 00:29:29.202
Oh, what's the use?

487
00:29:31.446 --> 00:29:32.470
What's the use?

488
00:29:32.647 --> 00:29:36.310
Hey. Hey, Ben, maybe
you'll get to like the Air Force.


489
00:29:36.485 --> 00:29:42.549
Zooming all over the sky and shouting
"roger" and "wilco" and everything.


490
00:29:42.724 --> 00:29:45.249
Maybe it won't be so bad.

491
00:29:45.794 --> 00:29:47.091
Bad?

492
00:29:47.262 --> 00:29:50.163
You know what they
call men in the Air Force?


493
00:29:50.332 --> 00:29:51.765
Airmen.

494
00:29:51.933 --> 00:29:54.163
Like something out
of a dang funny book.


495
00:29:54.336 --> 00:29:55.667
Airman.

496
00:29:55.837 --> 00:29:58.499
How you gonna like it when
somebody calls you "airman"?


497
00:29:58.940 --> 00:30:01.704
By dog, I just don't
think I'll stand for it.


498
00:30:01.877 --> 00:30:05.870
MAN 1: Hey, long as we gotta lie in the
dark, give us a chance to get some sleep.


499
00:30:06.047 --> 00:30:07.844
-Knock it off. MAN

500
00:30:08.016 --> 00:30:10.780
[MEN MURMURING]

501
00:30:10.952 --> 00:30:13.216
Airman.

502
00:30:17.592 --> 00:30:19.583
[TRUMPET PLAYING "TAPS"]

503
00:30:44.453 --> 00:30:47.047
Somebody brung their trumpet.

504
00:31:01.002 --> 00:31:02.993
[MEN SNORING]

505
00:31:18.353 --> 00:31:20.116
Hey, Ben.

506
00:31:20.789 --> 00:31:22.757
Hey. Hey, Ben.

507
00:31:47.015 --> 00:31:48.915
[MOANS]

508
00:31:49.684 --> 00:31:51.311
[LOUD KNOCKING ON DOOR]

509
00:31:51.486 --> 00:31:54.751
[MUTTERING]

510
00:31:55.257 --> 00:31:57.225
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

511
00:31:57.392 --> 00:32:00.589
All right, I'm up, I'm up. All
right, I'm up. All right, I'm up.


512
00:32:00.762 --> 00:32:02.161
All right, I'm up.

513
00:32:02.330 --> 00:32:03.524
Howdy, I'm Will Stockdale.

514
00:32:03.698 --> 00:32:06.064
I didn't hear the whistle.
Tell the men to line up.


515
00:32:06.234 --> 00:32:09.362
If the captain comes around, tell
him I'm checking on who overslept.


516
00:32:09.538 --> 00:32:12.666
I'll be out there just
as quick as I can....


517
00:32:16.111 --> 00:32:18.102
It's 12:00 at night.

518
00:32:18.547 --> 00:32:20.139
It is?

519
00:32:21.449 --> 00:32:22.973
Oh....

520
00:32:23.151 --> 00:32:26.643
That's a prettiest watch.

521
00:32:27.322 --> 00:32:28.812
You woke me.

522
00:32:29.324 --> 00:32:31.815
Well, you said to
knock before entering.


523
00:32:31.993 --> 00:32:34.427
Why did you wake me?

524
00:32:34.596 --> 00:32:37.121
This ain't nothing personal
against you, sergeant...


525
00:32:37.299 --> 00:32:40.325
...no, that we don't like your
barracks no, nothing like that.


526
00:32:40.502 --> 00:32:44.836
What it is, is Ben's got these
six brothers that's all infantry.


527
00:32:47.342 --> 00:32:49.606
That's my new buddy
Ben, that's asleep out there?


528
00:32:49.778 --> 00:32:53.009
So naturally, he don't wanna
be in no Air Force. Heh-heh.


529
00:32:55.750 --> 00:32:59.811
I mean, with the infantry doing the real
fighting and the Air Force being the helpers.


530
00:33:04.092 --> 00:33:07.619
Well, you know, like in the
War Between the States?


531
00:33:07.796 --> 00:33:11.425
So he wants to transfer and he
wants me to go along with him.


532
00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:14.364
I figured you could
do it for us. Heh-heh.


533
00:33:16.972 --> 00:33:18.564
I heard what you
said out there...


534
00:33:18.740 --> 00:33:23.177
...about how you was here to help us during
first difficult days of military service.


535
00:33:25.513 --> 00:33:30.450
Why do they send all the bums
and the idiots to my barracks?


536
00:33:31.119 --> 00:33:34.145
-They do?
-Yes.


537
00:33:34.823 --> 00:33:36.552
Yes, they do.

538
00:33:37.258 --> 00:33:39.453
Sure must be a mess.

539
00:33:40.996 --> 00:33:43.123
-Whatever your name is, get out--
-Stockdale.


540
00:33:43.298 --> 00:33:47.166
Stockdale, I want you to
get out of this-- Stockdale?


541
00:33:47.335 --> 00:33:49.064
Don't you come near me.

542
00:33:49.237 --> 00:33:52.764
Get out of this room and get back in
your bunk and go to sleep. That's all.


543
00:33:52.941 --> 00:33:54.568
Yes, sir.

544
00:33:55.543 --> 00:33:57.534
Ben did say the captain
was the one to see--


545
00:33:57.712 --> 00:34:00.044
-Stockdale, where you going?
-To the captain.


546
00:34:00.215 --> 00:34:01.773
Oh, no.

547
00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:05.249
But Ben, he knows all about
doing things military and--


548
00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:08.412
Oh, no. You can't,
you can't. You just:


549
00:34:08.590 --> 00:34:10.717
Oh, you can't do it.

550
00:34:10.892 --> 00:34:13.918
Captain would just as soon rip
off your stripes as look at you.


551
00:34:14.095 --> 00:34:16.495
-Well, I ain't got no stripes.
-Wait a minute.


552
00:34:16.965 --> 00:34:20.628
Now, you'll never get transfers
by waking up the captain.


553
00:34:20.802 --> 00:34:24.932
He won't understand.
Believe me, he won't.


554
00:34:26.041 --> 00:34:30.808
-Well, I'll go over it real slow.
-Wait a minute.


555
00:34:31.746 --> 00:34:34.647
Now, if you want the
captain to do you a favor...


556
00:34:34.816 --> 00:34:37.307
...you've gotta do a
favor for the captain.


557
00:34:37.485 --> 00:34:39.248
Yeah, that's it.

558
00:34:39.421 --> 00:34:42.151
Now, how would you like to
do a big favor for the captain?


559
00:34:42.323 --> 00:34:44.587
-Me?
-Come on. That's it.


560
00:34:44.759 --> 00:34:48.889
Come on. You do one for him, he'll
do one for me and I'll do one for you.


561
00:34:49.064 --> 00:34:53.228
That's the way it works out in the
service. Now you just go right on in here.


562
00:34:57.806 --> 00:35:01.742
Now do you know what this is?

563
00:35:02.077 --> 00:35:04.545
It's a kind of a big
outhouse, ain't it?


564
00:35:04.913 --> 00:35:08.781
-We call it the latrine.
-La-- Latrine.


565
00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:11.418
-Uh-huh.
-Heh. How about that?


566
00:35:11.586 --> 00:35:15.317
You might say it's the captain's hobby,
he inspects it every chance he gets.


567
00:35:15.490 --> 00:35:19.324
And when it sparkles,
why he sparkles too.


568
00:35:19.494 --> 00:35:21.553
Now, you get it all cleaned up.

569
00:35:21.730 --> 00:35:23.561
You are the officer in charge.

570
00:35:24.466 --> 00:35:25.956
In charge?

571
00:35:26.134 --> 00:35:29.467
Every last one
of them, all yours.


572
00:35:29.637 --> 00:35:32.435
Golly.

573
00:35:32.607 --> 00:35:35.770
Now, you just stay right
here and don't go no place.


574
00:35:35.944 --> 00:35:40.244
-You bet. Good night.
-Good night.


575
00:35:44.419 --> 00:35:46.683
Hey, thank you.

576
00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:53.728
Well, it just goes
to show you...


577
00:35:53.895 --> 00:35:57.592
...how good things happen to you
when you're least expecting them.


578
00:35:59.067 --> 00:36:02.366
Well, get started.

579
00:36:05.173 --> 00:36:08.836
WILL: I stayed officer in charge
of this here latrine all night long.


580
00:36:09.010 --> 00:36:10.807
Rubbing and scrubbing...

581
00:36:10.979 --> 00:36:15.040
...and doing my best to make
things sparkle like Sergeant King said.


582
00:36:15.216 --> 00:36:17.616
And then I stayed on
through breakfast too...


583
00:36:17.786 --> 00:36:20.778
...because I wanted to
do a right good job of it.


584
00:36:20.955 --> 00:36:23.753
So Sergeant King would be real
pleased how things come out...


585
00:36:23.925 --> 00:36:26.792
...when he come in to
look at it in the morning.


586
00:36:50.418 --> 00:36:51.976
Beautiful.

587
00:36:53.254 --> 00:36:56.246
Beautiful, beautiful, beautiful.

588
00:36:57.492 --> 00:37:00.552
-Beautiful.
-Shucks, it ain't hard.


589
00:37:00.728 --> 00:37:02.127
Wait'll the captain sees this.

590
00:37:02.297 --> 00:37:04.595
He inspects this like it
was an operating room...


591
00:37:04.766 --> 00:37:07.200
...where somebody was
gonna cut out his heart.


592
00:37:07.368 --> 00:37:12.237
Never in your life you've seen such a guy
for sticking his head right down into things.


593
00:37:12.407 --> 00:37:16.343
-You figure he'll like what I done?
-He'll be a new man.


594
00:37:18.646 --> 00:37:22.878
Will, how would you like to
be permanent latrine orderly?


595
00:37:24.052 --> 00:37:29.422
-Permanent latrine orderly?
-PLO.


596
00:37:30.625 --> 00:37:33.617
Golly.

597
00:37:33.795 --> 00:37:35.786
The captain makes
inspection every Saturday.


598
00:37:35.964 --> 00:37:38.899
Now, if you could keep everything
as clean as it is right now...


599
00:37:39.067 --> 00:37:41.627
...the captain'll
get off my back.


600
00:37:42.036 --> 00:37:44.732
Gee, I'd sure
like to, sergeant...


601
00:37:44.906 --> 00:37:49.070
...but I was kind of set on
helping Ben get them transfers.


602
00:37:49.244 --> 00:37:50.734
You know, he's my buddy.

603
00:37:52.614 --> 00:37:54.809
Ain't I your buddy?

604
00:37:55.383 --> 00:37:56.577
You are.

605
00:37:56.751 --> 00:37:59.049
You help me out, 
I'll help Ben.

606
00:37:59.220 --> 00:38:02.212
Just don't say anything
about this outside of this room.


607
00:38:02.390 --> 00:38:06.053
I'm going to the record section and
fix it up with a couple of friends of mine.


608
00:38:06.227 --> 00:38:07.888
Okay.

609
00:38:08.062 --> 00:38:12.260
Sergeant, don't I have to take them
tests you was talking about yesterday...


610
00:38:12.433 --> 00:38:14.162
...and get myself classified?

611
00:38:14.469 --> 00:38:18.530
No, Will, you've
been classified.


612
00:38:19.674 --> 00:38:21.665
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

613
00:38:27.715 --> 00:38:30.411
If we hurry, we can catch
that picture at the base theater.


614
00:38:30.585 --> 00:38:31.984
Not me, Ben.

615
00:38:32.153 --> 00:38:36.283
-You said you ain't never seen a picture.
-I know, but I got my duty to do.


616
00:38:39.727 --> 00:38:42.662
-You're going back to that latrine again?
-You bet.


617
00:38:42.830 --> 00:38:46.163
It's against the rules for you to be
permanent in the latrine like that.


618
00:38:46.334 --> 00:38:47.596
All week you've been there.

619
00:38:47.769 --> 00:38:49.634
Sergeant King knows
the rules, don't he?


620
00:38:49.804 --> 00:38:52.364
Besides, like I told you, he's
doing me and you a favor.


621
00:38:52.540 --> 00:38:56.772
-What favor, will you tell me that?
-I aim to surprise you, Ben.


622
00:38:56.945 --> 00:39:00.540
You don't go to lectures or study,
how you gonna get classified?


623
00:39:00.715 --> 00:39:02.740
Sergeant King says
I'm already that way.


624
00:39:02.917 --> 00:39:07.251
-Are you crazy? Don't you--?
-Now, don't take on so, Ben.


625
00:39:07.422 --> 00:39:11.119
Just wait and see what the captain says
after he makes his inspection tomorrow.


626
00:39:11.292 --> 00:39:13.351
Why you take them
faucets, for instance.


627
00:39:13.528 --> 00:39:17.328
I polished them so hard, they
don't say hot and cold no more.


628
00:39:19.033 --> 00:39:20.660
What?

629
00:39:26.207 --> 00:39:27.799
At ease.

630
00:39:31.946 --> 00:39:35.541
I think you'll be very
pleased here, sir.


631
00:39:35.717 --> 00:39:37.412
Attention.

632
00:39:42.357 --> 00:39:44.723
Latrine ready
for inspection, sir.


633
00:39:48.363 --> 00:39:52.732
This is incredible. This
is absolutely incredible.


634
00:39:52.900 --> 00:39:54.629
I am pleased.

635
00:39:54.802 --> 00:39:55.996
No.

636
00:39:56.170 --> 00:39:58.161
-No, I am happy.
-Thank you, sir. Thank you.


637
00:39:58.339 --> 00:40:01.206
-You the one on latrine duty today, private?
-Yes, sir. All week, sir.


638
00:40:01.376 --> 00:40:03.537
-Ahem, ahem.
-You are to be congratulated.


639
00:40:03.711 --> 00:40:05.838
Just look at--

640
00:40:06.681 --> 00:40:08.308
What did you say?

641
00:40:08.750 --> 00:40:10.945
Me? Nothing, sir.

642
00:40:11.519 --> 00:40:13.384
-Something about all week.
-Uh--


643
00:40:14.022 --> 00:40:18.186
Well, I done my best in one
day, but just to be fair with you...


644
00:40:18.359 --> 00:40:21.089
...it took me a week of
scrubbing to get it like this.


645
00:40:21.262 --> 00:40:23.389
Is this man being punished
for some infraction?


646
00:40:23.564 --> 00:40:27.591
-Oh, no, sir. No, sir.
-Oh, heck no, sir. I'm PLO.


647
00:40:28.803 --> 00:40:31.567
-You're what?
-Permanent latrine orderly.


648
00:40:31.739 --> 00:40:33.536
Stockdale.

649
00:40:33.708 --> 00:40:38.202
Oh, but don't credit me none though,
sir. It's all Sergeant King's doings.


650
00:40:38.379 --> 00:40:42.315
He even got it fixed up so I
don't even have to get classified.


651
00:40:42.483 --> 00:40:44.781
-Sir, l--
-What? That's impossible.


652
00:40:44.952 --> 00:40:48.388
Oh, no, sir. He fixed it
with some friends of his.


653
00:40:50.425 --> 00:40:53.155
Yes, sir. It was him
got me to work so hard...


654
00:40:53.327 --> 00:40:55.295
...telling me how
latrines is your hobby...


655
00:40:55.463 --> 00:40:58.398
...and sticking your head
down into things and all.


656
00:41:01.636 --> 00:41:06.972
-Sir, I can explain every--
-Now, don't you be bashful, sergeant.


657
00:41:08.576 --> 00:41:12.273
Sir, I been wanting to tell you
about what a good sergeant he is.


658
00:41:12.447 --> 00:41:15.473
Oh, he solves our
problems for us...


659
00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:19.950
...and helps us out on our
difficult days in military service.


660
00:41:20.121 --> 00:41:23.818
And I guess that he's about
the best dang sergeant there is...


661
00:41:23.991 --> 00:41:27.290
...in the whole
danged Air Force.


662
00:41:32.066 --> 00:41:35.797
Sir, you really ought
to get up off of his back.


663
00:41:43.878 --> 00:41:46.540
How long have you
been a sergeant?


664
00:41:47.915 --> 00:41:50.884
-Well, sir, l-- Ahem.
-Speak up.


665
00:41:51.652 --> 00:41:53.552
Sixteen years, sir.

666
00:41:53.721 --> 00:41:56.815
And how long do you
expect to remain a sergeant?


667
00:41:57.291 --> 00:41:58.315
Twelve years.

668
00:41:58.493 --> 00:42:01.428
You will remain a sergeant
exactly one week. One week.


669
00:42:01.596 --> 00:42:04.565
Unless this man completes
the entire classification process...


670
00:42:04.732 --> 00:42:07.724
...and is shipped out with the
group he came in with. Understand?


671
00:42:07.902 --> 00:42:10.632
Unless this man is out of
here by the end of the week...


672
00:42:10.805 --> 00:42:15.071
...you will not be in charge of this
barracks, you will not be a sergeant...


673
00:42:15.243 --> 00:42:19.202
...you will in all probability
be a permanent latrine orderly.


674
00:42:19.380 --> 00:42:22.178
PLO.

675
00:42:24.619 --> 00:42:26.849
This is not your fault, private.

676
00:42:27.288 --> 00:42:29.381
You've done a fine job.

677
00:42:30.224 --> 00:42:34.661
I have never seen such a
clean latrine in my entire career.


678
00:42:35.062 --> 00:42:36.154
Thank you, sir.

679
00:42:38.900 --> 00:42:42.028
It was my aim to get it just as
clean as that operating room...


680
00:42:42.203 --> 00:42:45.434
...where they're fixing
to cut out your heart!


681
00:42:51.145 --> 00:42:53.545
You forgot to ask him
about the transfers.


682
00:42:55.516 --> 00:42:59.247
What happened?
What did you do it for?


683
00:42:59.854 --> 00:43:02.880
Heck, I couldn't see no sense
in me getting all the credit.


684
00:43:07.361 --> 00:43:10.728
We've gotta get you classified right
away. We gotta get you out of here.


685
00:43:11.832 --> 00:43:14.926
You don't want me around no
more? I thought we was buddies.


686
00:43:15.803 --> 00:43:18.294
It ain't what I want, it's
what the captain wants.


687
00:43:18.472 --> 00:43:20.463
Now, we gotta get
you classified in a hurry.


688
00:43:20.641 --> 00:43:24.509
You're gonna have to take tests and you're
going to have to talk to a lot of people.


689
00:43:24.679 --> 00:43:27.443
And you're going to
have to work real hard.


690
00:43:28.382 --> 00:43:30.782
Will it help Ben and
me get them transfers?


691
00:43:30.952 --> 00:43:35.446
Well, I guarantee you, wherever you go,
they'll bust a gut to get you transferred.


692
00:43:35.623 --> 00:43:39.423
Well, I'll work hard all
right, but I don't know.


693
00:43:39.594 --> 00:43:42.324
The last test I took was
close on to five years ago...


694
00:43:42.496 --> 00:43:44.259
...and that was
one of them tests...


695
00:43:44.432 --> 00:43:46.957
...where you try this fella's
toothpaste for 10 days...


696
00:43:47.134 --> 00:43:50.103
...and see if your
teeth don't get brighter.


697
00:43:50.471 --> 00:43:52.439
And I failed.

698
00:43:53.474 --> 00:43:55.806
You been admiring this
watch of mine, haven't you?


699
00:43:55.977 --> 00:43:59.140
I sure have, sergeant. That there's
the prettiest watch I ever seen.


700
00:43:59.313 --> 00:44:02.646
You get shipped out of here by
Saturday morning like the captain said...


701
00:44:02.817 --> 00:44:04.216
...and it's yours.

702
00:44:04.385 --> 00:44:05.784
-Mine?
-Yours.


703
00:44:05.953 --> 00:44:09.081
Golly.

704
00:44:09.257 --> 00:44:11.782
-Now you'll work real hard, right?
-Right.


705
00:44:11.959 --> 00:44:13.722
-And not waste any time?
-No, sir.


706
00:44:13.894 --> 00:44:14.918
Good boy.

707
00:44:15.096 --> 00:44:17.656
Now first thing Monday
morning, we start classification.


708
00:44:17.832 --> 00:44:21.324
You stay right here around the
barracks and get a lot of rest...


709
00:44:21.502 --> 00:44:24.403
...and relax your head.

710
00:44:24.572 --> 00:44:30.238
I'm going down to the testing area
and see if I can borrow some of the tests.


711
00:44:30.411 --> 00:44:32.106
Okay.

712
00:44:33.748 --> 00:44:37.149
Tell them I'll give them back
just like I did the toothpaste.


713
00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:46.819
WILL: This place where they give
us the tests was really something.


714
00:44:46.994 --> 00:44:50.395
They had this great big building,
full of doctors, nurses and officers.


715
00:44:53.634 --> 00:44:56.569
All of them walking in and out
and around real quickety-quick...


716
00:44:56.737 --> 00:44:58.705
...and not smiling at nobody.

717
00:44:58.873 --> 00:45:01.967
And then there was this place
something like a schoolroom...


718
00:45:02.143 --> 00:45:05.203
...where they give us the
tests we had to write out.


719
00:45:05.379 --> 00:45:07.574
Time's up, pal.

720
00:45:15.856 --> 00:45:18.256
It was right friendly
of you to wait for me.


721
00:45:18.426 --> 00:45:20.155
Thank you.

722
00:45:21.962 --> 00:45:25.454
-How'd you think you did, Will?
-Well, them printed tests they give us...


723
00:45:25.633 --> 00:45:29.000
...they was exactly like the
ones that you borrowed--


724
00:45:31.205 --> 00:45:32.467
Only what?

725
00:45:32.640 --> 00:45:35.541
Only you spent so much time
drumming the answers into me...


726
00:45:35.710 --> 00:45:40.204
...we ought to have spent a little
more on the questions they joint up with.


727
00:45:45.152 --> 00:45:49.350
Now, you just sit right
down here and wait.


728
00:46:08.442 --> 00:46:11.070
Come on, Will, the
corporal's waiting.


729
00:46:17.585 --> 00:46:20.782
Here he is, corporal. Awfully
sorry to keep you waiting.


730
00:46:26.460 --> 00:46:29.452
What we do here, private, is to
evaluate your manual dexterity...


731
00:46:29.630 --> 00:46:33.930
...on a time scale in relation
to digital visual coordination.


732
00:46:34.101 --> 00:46:37.434
Two irregular steel links which
can be interconnected thusly.


733
00:46:37.605 --> 00:46:40.335
I separate them, I join them.

734
00:46:40.508 --> 00:46:42.738
It will be your task,
when I give the signal...


735
00:46:42.910 --> 00:46:45.811
...to place the two links in an
interconnected relationship...


736
00:46:45.980 --> 00:46:48.448
...I have just demonstrated.

737
00:46:54.955 --> 00:46:56.388
Uh....

738
00:46:56.891 --> 00:46:58.153
I put them together?

739
00:47:00.161 --> 00:47:02.629
That's right, you
put them together.


740
00:47:02.797 --> 00:47:05.288
I'll time you and three
minutes is passing.


741
00:47:05.466 --> 00:47:08.765
Now, whatever you
do, don't get nervous.


742
00:47:09.870 --> 00:47:12.338
Ready. Go.

743
00:47:16.544 --> 00:47:18.205
There you go.

744
00:47:19.213 --> 00:47:21.181
Attaboy.

745
00:47:22.783 --> 00:47:25.581
-Put them together.
-Sergeant, please.


746
00:47:25.753 --> 00:47:27.880
Nobody ever does this
in less than two minutes.


747
00:47:28.055 --> 00:47:30.114
You're not even
supposed to be in here.


748
00:47:30.291 --> 00:47:33.658
This is a special case. He has to
go out with the group he came in with.


749
00:47:33.828 --> 00:47:36.456
-It's is a very difficult test.
-I couldn't do it myself.


750
00:47:36.630 --> 00:47:39.394
-What are you talking about?
-I want you to get out of here.


751
00:47:39.567 --> 00:47:42.798
-I'd just like to see you try to do it.
-This is my department.


752
00:47:42.970 --> 00:47:45.131
-He's my department.
-That's my door. Get out.


753
00:47:45.306 --> 00:47:47.206
-Get out right this minute.
-Throw me out.


754
00:47:47.374 --> 00:47:49.638
You're not supposed to
be here. This is my watch--


755
00:47:49.810 --> 00:47:52.278
-All right, then watch your watch--
-I'm done.


756
00:47:52.446 --> 00:47:53.470
Stop the watch.

757
00:47:56.016 --> 00:47:59.884
-Look. Look at that.
-He put them together, didn't he?


758
00:48:00.888 --> 00:48:03.618
Sergeant! Sergeant!

759
00:48:03.791 --> 00:48:07.249
What's the fuss about? You said, "Put
them together," he put them together.


760
00:48:07.428 --> 00:48:10.522
Look what he did, for Pete's sake.
How am I gonna mark him on that?


761
00:48:10.698 --> 00:48:13.792
You're supposed to be grading
him on this. Can't you do that?


762
00:48:13.968 --> 00:48:17.301
I'm supposed to mark it down
whether they put it back together or not...


763
00:48:17.471 --> 00:48:21.066
...and there ain't supposed to be but
one way of doing it and he didn't do it.


764
00:48:21.242 --> 00:48:23.267
How you gonna mark
him on a thing like that?


765
00:48:23.444 --> 00:48:26.743
Who do you think's gonna pay for
these? Sixteen dollars, they cost.


766
00:48:26.914 --> 00:48:28.905
-lf you think I'm gonna pay $16--
-Corporal!


767
00:48:29.083 --> 00:48:30.107
Sixteen lousy dollars!

768
00:48:30.284 --> 00:48:33.776
Corporal, I'll be glad to
pay the 16 lousy dollars.


769
00:48:33.954 --> 00:48:35.683
-You will?
-lf he passed the test.


770
00:48:35.856 --> 00:48:38.620
He did it wrong. He was
supposed to do it a certain way.


771
00:48:38.792 --> 00:48:41.784
Will, will you step outside
for a minute, have a smoke.


772
00:48:46.066 --> 00:48:48.330
Now, corporal, let's
look at this thing logically.


773
00:48:48.502 --> 00:48:51.437
You need money and I
need him to pass the test.


774
00:48:51.605 --> 00:48:55.473
But he did do it
completely wrong.


775
00:49:00.147 --> 00:49:02.945
-Ben?
-Will.


776
00:49:03.117 --> 00:49:04.641
[CHUCKLES]

777
00:49:05.119 --> 00:49:07.679
I ain't seen you all day.
You been in there classifying?


778
00:49:07.855 --> 00:49:09.846
-Yeah.
-Me too. Find out where you're going?


779
00:49:10.024 --> 00:49:12.083
Sergeant King says
maybe gunnery school.


780
00:49:12.259 --> 00:49:14.523
That's where I'm going
too if I pass the eye test.


781
00:49:14.695 --> 00:49:17.493
-How about that?
-Yeah, how about that?


782
00:49:17.665 --> 00:49:21.396
Oh, Ben, you ain't still sad
about not being in the infantry?


783
00:49:21.569 --> 00:49:23.400
The captain didn't
even read my letter.


784
00:49:23.571 --> 00:49:25.766
And that plan of yours
sure didn't work so good.


785
00:49:25.940 --> 00:49:28.408
I tried to ask the psychiatrist
if he could fix me up.


786
00:49:28.576 --> 00:49:30.874
-Yeah, what'd he say?
-He didn't say nothing.


787
00:49:31.045 --> 00:49:33.138
I don't think he
understands so good.


788
00:49:33.581 --> 00:49:36.448
I'm just stuck in the
Air Force, that's all.


789
00:49:37.451 --> 00:49:40.648
Hey, Ben, maybe it's the Air
Force that's the real fighters...


790
00:49:40.821 --> 00:49:42.652
...and the infantry's
just the helpers.


791
00:49:42.823 --> 00:49:43.847
Never.

792
00:49:44.258 --> 00:49:46.522
Well, Ben, all you can
do is look at it that way.


793
00:49:46.694 --> 00:49:49.595
No. Wait'll my brothers
find out. Airman.


794
00:49:50.331 --> 00:49:52.026
Private.

795
00:49:52.199 --> 00:49:55.032
What kind of rowdydow
is this? Pick up that cap.


796
00:49:55.202 --> 00:49:56.226
Yes, sir.

797
00:49:56.403 --> 00:49:59.201
-Is that a way to treat government property?
-No, sir, ma'am.


798
00:49:59.373 --> 00:50:02.137
We're excited because we're
maybe going to the same school.


799
00:50:02.309 --> 00:50:04.504
That's no excuse for--

800
00:50:12.252 --> 00:50:14.482
What's the matter with this one?

801
00:50:16.590 --> 00:50:18.956
-Have you been drinking?
-No, no, sir.


802
00:50:19.126 --> 00:50:21.356
Get at attention, Will.

803
00:50:22.630 --> 00:50:24.894
We're sending this to school?

804
00:50:25.432 --> 00:50:28.993
Yes, sir, ma'am. If he passes the eye
test, he'll be going to gunnery school.


805
00:50:29.603 --> 00:50:32.333
As what? A target?

806
00:50:33.641 --> 00:50:34.801
No, sir, ma'am.

807
00:50:35.542 --> 00:50:38.477
Let's have no more rowdydow,
understand? No more.


808
00:50:38.646 --> 00:50:41.046
Yes, sir. Ma'am.

809
00:50:56.664 --> 00:50:58.723
What's the matter
with you, anyhow?


810
00:50:58.899 --> 00:51:02.096
Don't you know enough to come
to attention and salute an officer?


811
00:51:02.703 --> 00:51:04.227
-She was a woman.
-Sure she was.


812
00:51:04.405 --> 00:51:06.600
Ain't you ever heard of
the Women's Air Force?


813
00:51:06.774 --> 00:51:09.334
You mean they got one too?

814
00:51:09.877 --> 00:51:11.868
Sure.

815
00:51:12.112 --> 00:51:15.104
-Against ours?
-No, Will. They're with us.


816
00:51:15.282 --> 00:51:17.079
They're with us 100 percent.

817
00:51:17.251 --> 00:51:19.310
-We got to salute them?
-The officers, we do.


818
00:51:19.486 --> 00:51:22.455
Didn't you hear that lecture
about military courtesy?


819
00:51:22.623 --> 00:51:26.024
I'll be dogged. I never heard
of saluting no woman before.


820
00:51:26.193 --> 00:51:28.058
She ain't a woman,
she's a captain.


821
00:51:28.228 --> 00:51:30.992
I seen a captain there so I
come to attention and saluted.


822
00:51:31.165 --> 00:51:32.189
A captain, that's all.

823
00:51:32.366 --> 00:51:34.857
-A woman captain.
-A "captain" captain.


824
00:51:35.035 --> 00:51:37.731
By dog, don't you
understand nothing, Will?


825
00:51:37.905 --> 00:51:40.430
When you're in uniform,
you ain't supposed to notice...


826
00:51:40.607 --> 00:51:42.871
...whether a person is a
man or a woman or what.


827
00:51:43.043 --> 00:51:47.104
A captain's a captain, a major's
a major and a general's a general.


828
00:51:48.048 --> 00:51:52.678
Ben, you mean to tell me that you
didn't notice that she was a woman?


829
00:51:52.853 --> 00:51:55.447
A captain, that's all I seen.

830
00:51:55.622 --> 00:51:59.353
Well, dog it, Ben, I knew
she was a woman right off.


831
00:52:00.494 --> 00:52:04.590
Honest, Will, sometimes I wonder
how come they took you in the draft at all.


832
00:52:05.532 --> 00:52:06.999
Come on, Will.

833
00:52:07.167 --> 00:52:09.226
You too, Whitledge.

834
00:52:19.980 --> 00:52:23.916
Well, Will, it looks like you're
just liable to get classified after all.


835
00:52:24.084 --> 00:52:27.520
Just shows you what the
Air Force has come down to.


836
00:52:27.688 --> 00:52:30.851
-This the fella you want? Whitledge?
-Yeah.


837
00:52:31.024 --> 00:52:33.151
Psychiatrist says he
has a secondary anxiety...


838
00:52:33.327 --> 00:52:37.024
...with inferiority and systematized
delusions of persecution.


839
00:52:37.798 --> 00:52:38.958
I ain't surprised.

840
00:52:39.133 --> 00:52:42.534
Recommends he be considered
to be transferred to the infantry.


841
00:52:43.003 --> 00:52:44.334
The infantry?

842
00:52:44.505 --> 00:52:47.167
Don't get excited. He
didn't say you have to.


843
00:52:47.341 --> 00:52:51.641
Well, yeah, but that's what Ben's
always been wanting, corporal.


844
00:52:51.812 --> 00:52:56.181
-Just you tell me what I have to do.
-Well, here. Fill this out.


845
00:52:56.350 --> 00:52:59.285
When he's finished, buck it
through to the colonel for approval.


846
00:52:59.453 --> 00:53:01.080
If he's crazy enough to want it.

847
00:53:01.255 --> 00:53:03.018
How about that,
Ben? You made it.


848
00:53:03.190 --> 00:53:05.090
Just wait'll my
brothers hear about this.


849
00:53:05.259 --> 00:53:08.285
-Stockdale?
-Yeah.


850
00:53:11.098 --> 00:53:13.532
Okay, psychiatrist.

851
00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:15.565
Oh, Lord, psychiatrist.

852
00:53:17.037 --> 00:53:19.062
Now, Will, listen carefully.

853
00:53:20.440 --> 00:53:23.773
The psychiatrist test is one where
I couldn't get copies of questions...


854
00:53:23.944 --> 00:53:25.206
...because there ain't any.

855
00:53:25.379 --> 00:53:28.143
The doctor asks you whatever
happens to pop into his head.


856
00:53:28.315 --> 00:53:32.183
-So keep your wits about you.
-I'll try.


857
00:53:32.352 --> 00:53:33.944
Hey. Hey.

858
00:53:34.121 --> 00:53:37.682
Hey, maybe he'll give me
a transfer too, huh, Ben?


859
00:53:37.858 --> 00:53:41.316
He'll ask you things
like what do you dream?


860
00:53:41.495 --> 00:53:42.519
Okay.

861
00:53:42.696 --> 00:53:45.494
Hey, maybe he'll give me
a transfer too, huh, Ben?


862
00:53:45.666 --> 00:53:46.997
Sure, Will.

863
00:53:48.101 --> 00:53:52.561
-The psychiatrist is waiting, Stockdale.
-Coming.


864
00:53:55.042 --> 00:53:56.100
Wait a minute.

865
00:53:56.276 --> 00:53:59.268
The safest thing I guess is just
say that you never dream at all.


866
00:53:59.446 --> 00:54:03.075
-Okay. See you later, Ben.
-No dreams.


867
00:54:11.225 --> 00:54:12.783
Sergeant?

868
00:54:12.960 --> 00:54:14.450
Do you think he can?

869
00:54:14.628 --> 00:54:15.686
Can what?

870
00:54:15.863 --> 00:54:18.832
Get transferred too. Maybe
you could talk to the doctor.


871
00:54:18.999 --> 00:54:22.230
Now, don't you
complicate things.


872
00:54:34.548 --> 00:54:37.210
I never have no dreams at all.

873
00:54:44.157 --> 00:54:47.649
-Where are you from, Stockdale?
-Georgia.


874
00:54:48.562 --> 00:54:50.325
That's not much
of a state, is it?


875
00:54:50.497 --> 00:54:52.988
Well, I don't live
all over the state.


876
00:54:53.166 --> 00:54:56.465
I just live in this
one little place in it.


877
00:54:58.138 --> 00:55:03.041
That's where Tobacco
Road is. Georgia.


878
00:55:04.278 --> 00:55:06.405
Not around my section.

879
00:55:06.580 --> 00:55:08.844
Maybe you're from a
different part than me.


880
00:55:09.016 --> 00:55:10.643
[SIGHS]

881
00:55:10.984 --> 00:55:14.852
I've never been there. What's more, I
don't think I would ever wanna go there.


882
00:55:15.022 --> 00:55:16.512
What's your reaction to that?

883
00:55:16.690 --> 00:55:18.282
Well, I don't know--

884
00:55:18.458 --> 00:55:22.019
I would rather live in the rottenest
pigsty in Tennessee or Alabama...


885
00:55:22.195 --> 00:55:25.323
...than the fanciest
mansion in all of Georgia.


886
00:55:27.567 --> 00:55:29.296
How about that?

887
00:55:29.469 --> 00:55:34.270
Well, sir, I think where you
wanna live is your business.


888
00:55:38.378 --> 00:55:42.542
You don't mind if someone says
something bad about Georgia?


889
00:55:42.716 --> 00:55:45.446
I ain't heard nobody say
nothing bad about Georgia.


890
00:55:45.619 --> 00:55:48.144
Well, what do you
think I've been saying?


891
00:55:48.322 --> 00:55:51.416
Well, to tell you
the truth, sir...


892
00:55:51.591 --> 00:55:54.924
...I ain't been able to get
too much sense out of it.


893
00:55:57.898 --> 00:56:01.390
-Don't you know?
-Now, watch your steps, young man.


894
00:56:02.803 --> 00:56:05.237
Psychiatrists call this
attitude of yours resistance.


895
00:56:05.405 --> 00:56:06.667
-You do?
-Yes.


896
00:56:06.840 --> 00:56:10.241
You sense that this interview
is a threat to your security.


897
00:56:10.410 --> 00:56:14.346
-You feel yourself in danger.
-Well, kind of I do.


898
00:56:14.514 --> 00:56:16.141
If I don't get
myself classified...


899
00:56:16.316 --> 00:56:19.217
...Sergeant King, he won't
give me the wristwatch.


900
00:56:22.723 --> 00:56:24.315
He won't.

901
00:56:24.491 --> 00:56:29.292
He says I only get it if I'm
classified inside a week.


902
00:56:31.631 --> 00:56:36.227
Do you get along all
right with your mother?


903
00:56:36.403 --> 00:56:38.462
No, sir, I can't
hardly say that I do.


904
00:56:38.638 --> 00:56:42.597
Oh, I see. She's very strict with you.
She's always hovering over you. Hmm?


905
00:56:42.776 --> 00:56:45.074
-No, sir, just the opposite.
-She's never there?


906
00:56:45.245 --> 00:56:48.646
-That's right.
-And you resent this neglect, don't you?


907
00:56:48.815 --> 00:56:51.909
-Well, no, sir, I don't resent nothing.
-Oh, come now, son.


908
00:56:52.085 --> 00:56:55.111
Now, don't be bashful,
that's a common situation.


909
00:56:55.288 --> 00:56:58.416
-Does she beat you?
-No.


910
00:56:58.592 --> 00:56:59.889
[CHUCKLES]

911
00:57:00.060 --> 00:57:01.789
Oh, so defensive.

912
00:57:01.962 --> 00:57:04.760
Well, it's not easy to talk
about your mother, is it?


913
00:57:04.931 --> 00:57:07.195
No, sir. See, she
died when I was born.


914
00:57:16.643 --> 00:57:18.975
You could've told
me that sooner.


915
00:57:21.081 --> 00:57:23.345
Do you hate your mama?

916
00:57:24.484 --> 00:57:26.884
I figured as how you
said it was so common.


917
00:57:27.054 --> 00:57:29.716
I do not hate my mother.

918
00:57:30.357 --> 00:57:32.518
I should hope not.

919
00:57:33.960 --> 00:57:37.020
Does she beat you or something?

920
00:57:39.433 --> 00:57:40.491
This is a transference.

921
00:57:40.667 --> 00:57:44.899
You're taking your stored up antagonisms
and loosing them in my direction.


922
00:57:45.672 --> 00:57:48.835
Oh, transference. It
happens every day.


923
00:57:49.009 --> 00:57:52.911
-It does? To the infantry?
-Yeah--


924
00:57:53.513 --> 00:57:54.537
The infantry?

925
00:57:54.714 --> 00:57:57.649
You'd give Ben a transfer and
I wish you'd give me one too.


926
00:57:57.818 --> 00:58:01.754
-Because I'd sure love to go along with him.
-Now stop.


927
00:58:03.557 --> 00:58:06.253
Now, there are a few more
topics that we have to cover.


928
00:58:06.426 --> 00:58:09.691
We will not talk about transfers
and we will not talk about my mother.


929
00:58:09.863 --> 00:58:12.798
We will talk about
what I want to talk about.


930
00:58:13.500 --> 00:58:15.263
Do you understand?

931
00:58:15.502 --> 00:58:17.129
Yes, sir.

932
00:58:18.905 --> 00:58:20.532
Now, then.

933
00:58:20.707 --> 00:58:24.165
-Your father? Living?
-Yes, sir.


934
00:58:24.611 --> 00:58:25.908
Oh.

935
00:58:26.079 --> 00:58:29.139
-Do you get along with him okay?
-Yes, sir.


936
00:58:29.316 --> 00:58:32.774
-Does he ever beat you?
-Ha-ha. You bet.


937
00:58:32.953 --> 00:58:34.818
-Hard?
-And how.


938
00:58:34.988 --> 00:58:37.354
Boy, there ain't nobody
can beat like my pa can.


939
00:58:39.126 --> 00:58:41.458
So this is where the
antagonism comes from.


940
00:58:41.628 --> 00:58:42.652
[CHUCKLES]

941
00:58:42.829 --> 00:58:44.387
You hate your father, don't you?

942
00:58:45.665 --> 00:58:47.530
No.

943
00:58:47.834 --> 00:58:50.166
Hey, I got an
uncle I hate, though.


944
00:58:50.337 --> 00:58:54.068
Every time he comes out to the house,
he's wanting to wrestle with the mule...


945
00:58:54.241 --> 00:58:59.008
...and the mule gets all wore
out and he gets all wore out.


946
00:58:59.880 --> 00:59:02.849
Well, I don't really
hate him, though.


947
00:59:03.016 --> 00:59:06.042
It's just that I ain't
exactly partial to him.


948
00:59:06.953 --> 00:59:09.751
Did I ask you about your uncle?

949
00:59:10.557 --> 00:59:12.821
I thought you wanted to
talk about hating people.


950
00:59:12.993 --> 00:59:14.756
[SIGHS]

951
00:59:18.231 --> 00:59:21.200
Now. Now then.

952
00:59:22.335 --> 00:59:24.860
Um.... Girls.

953
00:59:25.038 --> 00:59:27.768
-How do you like girls?
-What girls is that, sir?


954
00:59:27.941 --> 00:59:32.469
Well, just girls.
Just any girls.


955
00:59:32.646 --> 00:59:37.106
Well, I don't
like just any girls.


956
00:59:37.284 --> 00:59:38.683
There's this girl back home...

957
00:59:38.852 --> 00:59:41.480
...that ain't got hair no longer
than a hound dog's and--


958
00:59:41.655 --> 00:59:44.215
Oh, no.

959
00:59:46.359 --> 00:59:48.691
When I say "girls," I don't
mean any specific girl.


960
00:59:48.862 --> 00:59:53.492
I just mean, well, girls in
general, you know? Heh. Heh.


961
00:59:53.667 --> 00:59:55.294
Women. Uh--

962
00:59:56.503 --> 00:59:58.164
Sex.

963
00:59:59.172 --> 01:00:02.630
Didn't that father of yours ever sit
you down and have a talk with you?


964
01:00:03.109 --> 01:00:04.940
Well, sure he did.

965
01:00:05.111 --> 01:00:06.772
Well?

966
01:00:07.614 --> 01:00:09.548
Well, what?

967
01:00:09.716 --> 01:00:12.549
Well, what did he say?

968
01:00:16.590 --> 01:00:19.855
[LAUGHS]

969
01:00:20.026 --> 01:00:24.395
Well, there's this one about
these two traveling salesmen.


970
01:00:24.564 --> 01:00:26.031
[BOTH LAUGH]

971
01:00:26.199 --> 01:00:29.293
And their car breaks down in
the middle of this terrible storm.


972
01:00:29.469 --> 01:00:31.733
-Stop.
-They come running up to this farmhouse...


973
01:00:31.905 --> 01:00:33.998
...where this farmer's
got these 14 daughters.


974
01:00:34.174 --> 01:00:35.801
-Stop.
-Uh--


975
01:00:36.776 --> 01:00:38.903
Did you heared it already?

976
01:00:39.613 --> 01:00:41.706
I did not heared it already.

977
01:00:41.881 --> 01:00:44.645
What'd you stop me for?
It's a real knee-slapper.


978
01:00:44.818 --> 01:00:48.151
See, these 14 daughters was all
studying to become trombone players--


979
01:00:48.321 --> 01:00:49.948
Here, look. You
go. You're through.


980
01:00:50.123 --> 01:00:53.581
You're perfectly normal. Just
go. Goodbye. Go. Goodbye.


981
01:00:59.766 --> 01:01:01.233
Excuse me for saying it, sir...

982
01:01:01.401 --> 01:01:04.859
...but I don't think a fella your age
would be so confused about it all...


983
01:01:05.038 --> 01:01:07.598
...if you went out and seen
some girls once in a while.


984
01:01:08.308 --> 01:01:10.833
Look, out. Out!

985
01:01:11.478 --> 01:01:13.139
Yes, sir.

986
01:01:18.318 --> 01:01:20.809
Fella's in pretty bad shape.

987
01:01:25.558 --> 01:01:28.493
-Where's Sergeant King?
-He said he'd meet you in the mess hall.


988
01:01:28.662 --> 01:01:31.222
Something about he couldn't stand
the strain on an empty stomach.


989
01:01:31.398 --> 01:01:33.559
Oh. Thank you.

990
01:01:34.200 --> 01:01:36.031
-Stockdale, Will.
-Here.


991
01:01:36.202 --> 01:01:37.692
Eye test in here.

992
01:01:37.871 --> 01:01:39.896
I can't. I gotta tell
Sergeant King that--


993
01:01:40.073 --> 01:01:42.564
Get in there,
Stockdale, on the double.


994
01:01:44.044 --> 01:01:47.810
Yes, sir. Just be an
extra surprise for him.


995
01:01:53.386 --> 01:01:55.786
What's keeping him so long?

996
01:01:55.955 --> 01:01:59.356
He's probably telling the psychiatrist
how he dreams about his pet horse.


997
01:01:59.526 --> 01:02:01.494
Oh, cut it out, will you?

998
01:02:01.661 --> 01:02:04.459
Ain't I got enough,
sweating this out?


999
01:02:04.831 --> 01:02:07.459
Sergeant, can I have
my application a minute?


1000
01:02:08.868 --> 01:02:11.564
I got a feeling I'm
doomed. I'm doomed.


1001
01:02:11.738 --> 01:02:13.569
Of all the....

1002
01:02:16.242 --> 01:02:19.769
-What the heck you doing that for?
-Guess I changed my mind.


1003
01:02:19.946 --> 01:02:23.438
This whole thing started from
you hollering to get into the infantry.


1004
01:02:23.616 --> 01:02:25.550
I changed my mind.

1005
01:02:26.119 --> 01:02:28.815
Why do I get all the nuts?

1006
01:02:31.358 --> 01:02:32.382
There he is.

1007
01:02:33.226 --> 01:02:35.285
Hey, Will, come here, will you?

1008
01:02:35.462 --> 01:02:37.726
Sorry to keep y'all waiting
so long. Pete, Irving.


1009
01:02:37.897 --> 01:02:41.389
Well, what happened, boy?
How'd you do? Where's the form?


1010
01:02:42.035 --> 01:02:43.400
Well, let me see it.

1011
01:02:43.570 --> 01:02:45.902
I wanna see what he had....

1012
01:02:49.476 --> 01:02:52.673
He passed. He got through.

1013
01:02:53.346 --> 01:02:55.211
He's normal.

1014
01:02:55.582 --> 01:02:57.482
Attaboy.

1015
01:02:57.650 --> 01:03:01.086
Yes, sir, you ought to see the way
Will breezes through these tests.


1016
01:03:01.254 --> 01:03:03.620
One, two, three. Bim-bam-boom.

1017
01:03:04.090 --> 01:03:08.026
Tomorrow morning, I'm gonna run
him down to the little old eye test...


1018
01:03:08.194 --> 01:03:10.822
...and by tomorrow
night, he's out of here.


1019
01:03:11.197 --> 01:03:15.327
Gunnery school, well, Will
boy? With your eyesight.


1020
01:03:15.935 --> 01:03:20.565
This boy told me that he could shoot
the eye out of a turkey at a 100 yards?


1021
01:03:21.541 --> 01:03:23.099
I already took the eye test.

1022
01:03:23.743 --> 01:03:26.644
Uh.... What?

1023
01:03:29.315 --> 01:03:31.112
Fella grabbed me
on the way over here.


1024
01:03:31.918 --> 01:03:35.081
Well, what happened?
Where's the form? Papers?


1025
01:03:35.922 --> 01:03:39.449
Fella back there kept the papers,
on account I was the last test.


1026
01:03:40.193 --> 01:03:42.957
He said it'd all come out on
the bulletin board tomorrow.


1027
01:03:43.296 --> 01:03:45.696
Well, how'd you do?
You passed, didn't you?


1028
01:03:46.299 --> 01:03:47.926
-Easy, huh?
-I don't know.


1029
01:03:48.101 --> 01:03:51.002
He seemed kind of
angry most of the time.


1030
01:03:51.704 --> 01:03:53.672
What made you
think he was angry?


1031
01:03:58.711 --> 01:04:00.338
Well, he got sort of fussed...

1032
01:04:00.513 --> 01:04:03.880
...when I was reading this
here sign they had on the wall.


1033
01:04:04.050 --> 01:04:06.484
And that was
right hard at first...


1034
01:04:06.653 --> 01:04:09.816
...because they was
real peculiar words like:


1035
01:04:09.989 --> 01:04:13.550
Ip, gnxl and buglump.

1036
01:04:17.397 --> 01:04:21.026
You were supposed to read
them letters one at a time.


1037
01:04:21.434 --> 01:04:23.994
Didn't make much
sense that way neither.


1038
01:04:25.238 --> 01:04:27.433
Hey, hey, hey.

1039
01:04:27.607 --> 01:04:31.475
Take a look at the colonel and the
wife captain that come in the base.


1040
01:04:32.612 --> 01:04:34.807
Boy, is she stacked.

1041
01:04:34.981 --> 01:04:38.007
IRVING: Women officers, that's
one thing I sure don't cotton to.


1042
01:04:38.184 --> 01:04:39.481
What about you, Stockdale?

1043
01:04:39.652 --> 01:04:42.348
-What do you think of them?
-I ain't never seen one.


1044
01:04:42.522 --> 01:04:43.989
Ain't you got eyes?

1045
01:04:46.459 --> 01:04:50.919
Will, I want you to turn
around very slowly...


1046
01:04:51.097 --> 01:04:56.967
...and look very carefully this time
and tell me exactly what you see.


1047
01:05:03.910 --> 01:05:08.904
I see a colonel....

1048
01:05:09.082 --> 01:05:10.743
Yeah.

1049
01:05:11.451 --> 01:05:13.180
And a captain.

1050
01:05:13.686 --> 01:05:14.744
That's all.

1051
01:05:15.889 --> 01:05:17.686
And the captain's
a woman, isn't she?


1052
01:05:18.324 --> 01:05:23.728
I don't notice whether it's
a man or a woman or what.


1053
01:05:24.097 --> 01:05:27.430
All I see is a
captain. That's all.


1054
01:05:28.368 --> 01:05:29.858
Yeah.

1055
01:05:31.571 --> 01:05:33.766
Oh, no, no, no.

1056
01:05:34.774 --> 01:05:37.675
What's the matter, sergeant,
you got a fly in your coffee?


1057
01:05:37.844 --> 01:05:40.813
-Can I get you some fresh hot?
-Oh, no, no, Will. No.


1058
01:05:40.980 --> 01:05:43.915
Just go on your way.

1059
01:05:44.083 --> 01:05:49.578
-Your own special way.
-Thanks, sergeant.


1060
01:05:51.124 --> 01:05:55.493
Hey, it sure makes me proud to know
you're sure about me getting classified.


1061
01:05:58.531 --> 01:06:00.999
He sure didn't pass no eye test.

1062
01:06:01.167 --> 01:06:04.102
And he ain't
gonna be classified.


1063
01:06:05.605 --> 01:06:09.268
And I'm gonna be
permanent latrine orderly.


1064
01:06:12.445 --> 01:06:15.380
How big do they grow
them turkeys down there?


1065
01:06:16.215 --> 01:06:18.615
No, he can't do this to me.

1066
01:06:18.785 --> 01:06:20.685
I'm old and I'm tired...

1067
01:06:20.853 --> 01:06:23.447
...and my constitution
needs peace and security.


1068
01:06:23.623 --> 01:06:25.989
Look, sarge. Sarge.

1069
01:06:26.159 --> 01:06:28.127
If he wasn't to
get classified...


1070
01:06:28.294 --> 01:06:31.161
...and it wasn't your fault,
that'd be all right, wouldn't it?


1071
01:06:31.331 --> 01:06:32.958
How? How?

1072
01:06:33.132 --> 01:06:36.761
Supposing he didn't show
up for inspection tomorrow?


1073
01:06:36.936 --> 01:06:41.805
And when he finally did show,
he'd been drinking, shall we say?


1074
01:06:42.976 --> 01:06:46.343
Listen, Irving, I even got
so I kind of like the kid.


1075
01:06:46.512 --> 01:06:50.278
And I ain't one to go too
far outside regulations.


1076
01:06:51.217 --> 01:06:55.313
But if you got an
idea, I'm desperate.


1077
01:06:55.488 --> 01:06:58.616
All you gotta do is
wangle us three passes.


1078
01:06:58.791 --> 01:07:02.454
We'll take him to the Purple
Grotto for a little celebration.


1079
01:07:04.597 --> 01:07:07.430
We could take him tonight.

1080
01:07:07.900 --> 01:07:10.164
Yeah, we could.

1081
01:07:10.470 --> 01:07:12.461
[LOUD MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS INSIDE]


1082
01:07:43.803 --> 01:07:47.830
Well, Will, here we
are again. Round two.


1083
01:07:48.007 --> 01:07:49.668
I sure do appreciate this.

1084
01:07:49.842 --> 01:07:53.209
I still don't feel right, my glass
being so much bigger than you alls.


1085
01:07:53.379 --> 01:07:56.974
Guest of honor always gets the
biggest glass. That's the honor.


1086
01:07:57.150 --> 01:07:58.981
-To Will.
-To Will.


1087
01:07:59.152 --> 01:08:00.619
-Again?
-Come on, come on, come on.


1088
01:08:00.787 --> 01:08:04.621
Ha-ha-ha. Whee.

1089
01:08:16.269 --> 01:08:20.069
Your Scotch stuff tastes kind of sharp.
I like the other stuff you give me better.


1090
01:08:20.239 --> 01:08:23.003
-You mean the bourbon?
-No, gin.


1091
01:08:29.949 --> 01:08:33.407
Yeah. More tangy than sharp.

1092
01:08:35.221 --> 01:08:38.657
Sure was nice of you to give me
this celebration party, sergeant.


1093
01:08:39.225 --> 01:08:42.251
But I still wish Ben
could've come along too.


1094
01:08:42.662 --> 01:08:44.220
Just couldn't wangle it.

1095
01:08:44.397 --> 01:08:48.697
Outside of you, Ben's the only one left
responsible enough for barracks duty.


1096
01:08:48.868 --> 01:08:52.167
And tomorrow, we got a real
inspection. The colonel's coming.


1097
01:08:52.338 --> 01:08:56.069
Yeah, Ben's sharp. Come
on, Will, drink it up. Drink it up.


1098
01:09:02.181 --> 01:09:04.240
[EXHALES]

1099
01:09:04.650 --> 01:09:07.244
Well, I reckon we ought
to be heading on back.


1100
01:09:07.420 --> 01:09:09.047
With the colonel
coming tomorrow...


1101
01:09:09.222 --> 01:09:13.454
...I wanna give Ben a hand and get
the barracks cleaned up real special.


1102
01:09:13.626 --> 01:09:15.491
Wait a minute, wait a minute.

1103
01:09:15.661 --> 01:09:19.028
I told you I was gonna give you my
watch and I'm gonna give you my watch.


1104
01:09:19.198 --> 01:09:21.428
We gotta have several,
several drinks on that.


1105
01:09:21.601 --> 01:09:23.501
Golly.

1106
01:09:25.772 --> 01:09:27.831
My mother gave it to me.

1107
01:09:28.474 --> 01:09:30.408
To Will Stockdale...

1108
01:09:30.576 --> 01:09:34.307
...I am proud of him for
getting classified so good...


1109
01:09:34.480 --> 01:09:37.313
...and for cleaning
up the latrine and all.


1110
01:09:37.483 --> 01:09:40.384
Thank you.

1111
01:09:40.553 --> 01:09:43.852
Thank you.

1112
01:09:45.958 --> 01:09:48.518
Whoo-hoo!

1113
01:09:49.128 --> 01:09:51.221
To Sergeant King.

1114
01:09:51.998 --> 01:09:54.193
The best dang
sergeant there is...


1115
01:09:54.367 --> 01:09:58.963
...in the whole
danged Air Force.


1116
01:10:05.711 --> 01:10:07.178
Ahhh.

1117
01:10:08.514 --> 01:10:12.382
By dog, from a jug, it don't
taste sharp at all, does it?


1118
01:10:13.719 --> 01:10:18.179
Will, are you absolutely sure that you
never drank any whiskey before, at all?


1119
01:10:18.357 --> 01:10:21.815
Never no store whiskey, just
some old stuff my pa makes.


1120
01:10:22.195 --> 01:10:25.062
-Some old stuff that your pa--
-Yeah.


1121
01:10:25.231 --> 01:10:26.755
Corn liquor kind of.

1122
01:10:26.933 --> 01:10:30.596
You know, corn, grain, kerosene.

1123
01:10:30.770 --> 01:10:31.930
-Kerosene?
-Kerosene?


1124
01:10:33.239 --> 01:10:35.230
Just a mite for flavoring.

1125
01:10:35.408 --> 01:10:37.706
Where the heck are we
gonna get some kerosene?


1126
01:10:37.877 --> 01:10:39.845
WOMAN: Cigars, cigarettes?

1127
01:10:40.012 --> 01:10:42.776
And anything else
you wanna smoke.


1128
01:10:42.949 --> 01:10:45.850
Cigars, cigarettes?

1129
01:10:49.055 --> 01:10:51.250
Why, thank you.

1130
01:10:52.625 --> 01:10:55.617
-This ought to come near it.
-Sure.


1131
01:10:56.562 --> 01:11:00.828
He wants kerosene,
he gets kerosene.


1132
01:11:07.073 --> 01:11:08.631
It's familiar.

1133
01:11:11.844 --> 01:11:15.712
Hey, there's a
infan-- Hey, infantry.


1134
01:11:16.883 --> 01:11:17.907
Hi.

1135
01:11:18.084 --> 01:11:19.915
Let's drink one to the infantry.

1136
01:11:23.789 --> 01:11:26.883
-Have a drink. We're celebrating.
-Hi, Jack.


1137
01:11:27.059 --> 01:11:30.028
Thanks a lot. I
do not mind if I do.


1138
01:11:30.196 --> 01:11:32.960
-To the infantry.
-To the infantry.


1139
01:11:33.499 --> 01:11:36.127
To the infantry.

1140
01:11:54.086 --> 01:11:57.578
So....

1141
01:11:58.691 --> 01:12:03.128
Say, I didn't know you fly
boys were so nice to the infantry.


1142
01:12:03.296 --> 01:12:06.663
Hey, heck, it's the air age and
you're our helpers, ain't you?


1143
01:12:06.832 --> 01:12:10.290
-Your what?
-Our helpers.


1144
01:12:10.469 --> 01:12:13.029
Don't think we don't
appreciate it too.


1145
01:12:13.205 --> 01:12:17.232
Listen, listen, fellas.
You're a nice bunch of fellas.


1146
01:12:17.410 --> 01:12:23.315
Fellas, you got it easier
than anybody, even the Navy.


1147
01:12:23.482 --> 01:12:24.642
Easy.

1148
01:12:24.817 --> 01:12:29.481
We got the roughest, toughest,
meanest sergeants in the whole service.


1149
01:12:29.655 --> 01:12:31.213
Go on.

1150
01:12:31.390 --> 01:12:35.850
You don't know what a tough sergeant
is until you've been in the infantry.


1151
01:12:36.028 --> 01:12:41.193
Ain't nobody tougher than
my sergeant. He's tough.


1152
01:12:41.367 --> 01:12:43.631
I sure am.

1153
01:12:43.803 --> 01:12:45.327
Oh, sergeant.

1154
01:12:46.005 --> 01:12:47.404
I'm a louse.

1155
01:12:47.573 --> 01:12:49.598
I don't know, sergeant.

1156
01:12:49.775 --> 01:12:54.235
You seem to be a
pretty decent Joe to me.


1157
01:12:54.814 --> 01:12:58.477
-You take that back.
-All right.


1158
01:12:58.651 --> 01:13:00.209
I'll just bet you five bucks...

1159
01:13:00.386 --> 01:13:03.321
...I'm a bigger louse than
you and I'm just a private.


1160
01:13:03.489 --> 01:13:07.016
-Yeah? Put up or shut up.
-Yeah, put up or shut up.


1161
01:13:07.193 --> 01:13:10.492
What's a bigger louse than a
louse that'll drink your booze...


1162
01:13:10.663 --> 01:13:12.654
...and then punch
you right in the guts?


1163
01:13:12.832 --> 01:13:16.393
-Put up or shut up.
-Oh, says who?


1164
01:13:16.569 --> 01:13:18.901
Sergeant, I think we ought
to be going on back now.


1165
01:13:19.071 --> 01:13:21.130
KING: Go away, you're drunk.

1166
01:13:23.876 --> 01:13:25.036
Oh-ho.

1167
01:13:25.211 --> 01:13:27.236
SOLDIER: Come on,
infantry, let's get the fly boys.


1168
01:13:27.413 --> 01:13:29.005
Oh....

1169
01:13:29.181 --> 01:13:31.172
[WOMEN SCREAMING]

1170
01:13:33.619 --> 01:13:35.382
[LAUGHS]

1171
01:13:35.554 --> 01:13:37.181
Oh!

1172
01:13:40.359 --> 01:13:44.989
I done hit him once, Irving,
ain't no use to overdoing it.


1173
01:13:51.737 --> 01:13:54.262
Now, you see, you
antagonized him, sergeant.


1174
01:13:54.440 --> 01:13:56.499
I think we ought to be
going on home, anyhow.


1175
01:13:56.675 --> 01:13:59.007
All right, just a minute.

1176
01:13:59.912 --> 01:14:01.903
[GRUNTING]

1177
01:14:08.387 --> 01:14:10.355
I know you're having
a whole lot of fun...


1178
01:14:10.523 --> 01:14:12.491
...so I won't stay around
and be a wet blanket.


1179
01:14:12.658 --> 01:14:13.920
[MUTTERING]

1180
01:14:14.093 --> 01:14:16.152
Okay, I'm going on
back to the barracks.


1181
01:14:16.328 --> 01:14:17.352
[MUTTERING]

1182
01:14:17.530 --> 01:14:20.829
Hush a minute, hush a minute. I'm
gonna go on back and give Ben a hand.


1183
01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:23.798
[MUTTERING]

1184
01:14:46.692 --> 01:14:50.128
-Is this the Purple Grotto?
-Right up yonder.


1185
01:14:55.901 --> 01:14:58.461
Couple of thirsty
fellas for you.


1186
01:15:09.281 --> 01:15:11.181
[WHISTLING]

1187
01:15:14.487 --> 01:15:16.853
-Ain't the sergeant showed up yet?
-Nope.


1188
01:15:17.022 --> 01:15:20.514
-Why didn't you come to breakfast?
-Went over to carpenter shop.


1189
01:15:20.693 --> 01:15:23.218
-What're you doing there?
-Fixing up something special.


1190
01:15:23.395 --> 01:15:25.625
It ain't everyday a
colonel comes to inspect.


1191
01:15:25.798 --> 01:15:27.732
I sure wish the
sergeant was here.


1192
01:15:27.900 --> 01:15:31.097
Like I told you, he was having a
whole lot of fun. But he'll show up.


1193
01:15:31.270 --> 01:15:34.535
Sergeant King, he ain't gonna
miss no inspection if he can help it.


1194
01:15:35.141 --> 01:15:36.768
The heck he ain't.

1195
01:15:36.942 --> 01:15:40.241
Here comes the captain
now. And the colonel.


1196
01:15:40.412 --> 01:15:43.973
-Going round front.
-Oh, golly.


1197
01:15:44.950 --> 01:15:47.612
-Who's gonna report?
-Hey, you're in charge.


1198
01:15:47.786 --> 01:15:49.879
-Me?
-Yeah.


1199
01:15:50.789 --> 01:15:53.257
BEN: Barracks ready
for inspection, sir.


1200
01:15:53.626 --> 01:15:55.719
-Barracks ready for inspection, sir.
-Here.


1201
01:15:55.895 --> 01:15:59.763
Listen, when you throw open this door,
holler "Attention," just as loud as you can.


1202
01:15:59.932 --> 01:16:01.559
Okay? Okay. Okay.

1203
01:16:08.274 --> 01:16:10.401
Barracks ready
for inspection, sir.


1204
01:16:12.678 --> 01:16:13.770
Where's Sergeant King?

1205
01:16:13.946 --> 01:16:16.915
I don't know, sir, but the
barracks are ready for inspection.


1206
01:16:17.082 --> 01:16:18.982
All right, all right.

1207
01:16:19.852 --> 01:16:22.787
Just for a starter, I'd like you
to take a look at this latrine.


1208
01:16:22.955 --> 01:16:26.220
There's a man in this barracks
whose latrine work is quite surprising.


1209
01:16:26.992 --> 01:16:31.429
Attention!

1210
01:16:34.333 --> 01:16:36.995
Latrine ready
for inspection, sir.


1211
01:16:52.685 --> 01:16:55.449
Latrine ready
for inspection, sir.


1212
01:17:00.025 --> 01:17:02.585
What is the idea behind this?

1213
01:17:04.430 --> 01:17:06.796
Welcoming the colonel, sir.

1214
01:17:09.368 --> 01:17:10.801
I'm sorry, sir.

1215
01:17:10.970 --> 01:17:15.771
Oh, that's all right, captain. I've
been welcomed in many ways.


1216
01:17:15.941 --> 01:17:19.172
Ticker tape, flags waving.

1217
01:17:19.345 --> 01:17:22.906
Women of a French village
once three rose buds at me.


1218
01:17:23.082 --> 01:17:25.016
But this....

1219
01:17:26.151 --> 01:17:28.176
This is just....

1220
01:17:29.021 --> 01:17:31.455
Well, I don't know.

1221
01:17:42.001 --> 01:17:44.765
They didn't hardly
inspect the latrine at all.


1222
01:17:44.937 --> 01:17:46.632
I don't know, Will.

1223
01:17:46.805 --> 01:17:48.295
They--

1224
01:17:48.874 --> 01:17:50.933
They, oh....

1225
01:18:19.872 --> 01:18:21.737
Sergeant.

1226
01:18:22.608 --> 01:18:24.838
Lieutenant back there
almost spotted me.


1227
01:18:25.010 --> 01:18:26.841
-You all right?
-I ain't sure.


1228
01:18:27.012 --> 01:18:29.173
-Hey, where's Irving?
-MP's got him.


1229
01:18:29.348 --> 01:18:31.646
-Golly. COLONEL:
Very nice, captain.


1230
01:18:31.817 --> 01:18:33.148
CAPTAIN: Thank you, sir.

1231
01:18:33.319 --> 01:18:34.684
-The colonel?
-Yeah.


1232
01:18:34.853 --> 01:18:37.822
Hey, they inspected
in here already.


1233
01:18:38.023 --> 01:18:39.047
Hey...

1234
01:18:39.224 --> 01:18:41.488
...watch out for that treadle.

1235
01:18:44.263 --> 01:18:46.322
COLONEL: Very good, indeed.

1236
01:18:49.902 --> 01:18:54.999
Mm-hm. Excellent. Excellent. Were you
in charge during your sergeant's absence?


1237
01:18:55.174 --> 01:18:56.641
Yes, sir. Complete charge.

1238
01:18:56.809 --> 01:18:59.073
I think you should make
a note of this man's name.


1239
01:18:59.244 --> 01:19:00.268
Yes, indeed, sir.

1240
01:19:00.446 --> 01:19:02.175
-What is it, private?
-Whitledge, sir.


1241
01:19:12.791 --> 01:19:13.917
Whitledge, sir.

1242
01:19:14.093 --> 01:19:16.391
-What's that again, private?
-Whitledge, sir.


1243
01:19:16.562 --> 01:19:22.262
W
-H-l
-T
-L
-E
-D
-G
-E.

1244
01:19:24.803 --> 01:19:28.068
-What the devil is--?
-What's going on in there?


1245
01:19:28.741 --> 01:19:31.107
Latrine's out of order, sir.

1246
01:19:31.276 --> 01:19:33.710
You're gonna have to
use the one next door.


1247
01:19:33.879 --> 01:19:35.676
Let me in there.

1248
01:19:44.390 --> 01:19:47.086
This is the barracks
sergeant, sir.


1249
01:19:48.227 --> 01:19:50.092
How are you, sir?

1250
01:19:50.262 --> 01:19:53.390
All slicked up for
inspection. Explain.


1251
01:19:55.768 --> 01:19:57.395
Explain.

1252
01:19:58.137 --> 01:19:59.934
Well, sir...

1253
01:20:01.039 --> 01:20:03.837
...I went to a
movie last night, sir.


1254
01:20:04.009 --> 01:20:07.501
And there were these eight
infantry men sitting right in behind me.


1255
01:20:07.679 --> 01:20:10.045
And they was cussing
out the Air Force...


1256
01:20:10.215 --> 01:20:15.482
...and saying as how that their officers
were more understanding than our officers.


1257
01:20:15.654 --> 01:20:21.615
-So you fought them all night long?
-Yes, sir, it was awful.


1258
01:20:22.161 --> 01:20:24.152
What was the name of the movie?

1259
01:20:24.830 --> 01:20:25.922
-Movie?
-The movie.


1260
01:20:26.098 --> 01:20:27.565
Oh.

1261
01:20:29.134 --> 01:20:31.159
Forward March.

1262
01:20:31.837 --> 01:20:34.169
American Battalion.

1263
01:20:34.406 --> 01:20:36.271
Out of the Air.

1264
01:20:37.743 --> 01:20:40.211
Up in the Wild Blue?

1265
01:20:41.447 --> 01:20:43.608
It was a sneak preview.

1266
01:20:45.150 --> 01:20:47.880
Captain, I don't know how
this man ever got on my base...


1267
01:20:48.053 --> 01:20:50.180
...but he's certainly not
going to remain here.


1268
01:20:50.355 --> 01:20:54.348
Corrupting new airmen with this
horrible example. Ship him out.


1269
01:20:54.526 --> 01:20:56.790
There's a group leaving
for gunnery school today.


1270
01:20:56.962 --> 01:21:00.090
Splendid. General Bush can
always use another private.


1271
01:21:00.265 --> 01:21:01.823
Private?

1272
01:21:04.303 --> 01:21:05.770
Private.

1273
01:21:07.139 --> 01:21:08.731
Private.

1274
01:21:10.943 --> 01:21:12.535
BEN: That name
was Whitledge, sir.


1275
01:21:12.711 --> 01:21:14.576
W
-H-l
-T
-L--

1276
01:21:14.746 --> 01:21:16.077
-Whitledge, eh?
-Yes, sir.


1277
01:21:16.248 --> 01:21:20.912
This is going on your record, Whitledge.
This is going on everybody's record.


1278
01:21:26.225 --> 01:21:29.626
Something special
for the colonel.


1279
01:21:33.565 --> 01:21:35.692
You ain't a sergeant no more.

1280
01:21:35.868 --> 01:21:38.632
No, I ain't a sergeant
no more. I'm a private.


1281
01:21:38.804 --> 01:21:42.240
A 45-year-old private.

1282
01:21:42.608 --> 01:21:43.870
Gosh.

1283
01:21:44.042 --> 01:21:47.375
-He's putting it on my record.
-Gosh, Ben--


1284
01:21:47.546 --> 01:21:51.539
There's one silver lining to
this cloud, though, by George.


1285
01:21:51.717 --> 01:21:55.483
You're staying here, but
I'm going to gunnery school...


1286
01:21:55.654 --> 01:21:58.248
...a thousand miles away.

1287
01:21:58.423 --> 01:21:59.913
WILL: Sergeant?
-Private.


1288
01:22:00.092 --> 01:22:01.491
I ain't staying here.

1289
01:22:01.660 --> 01:22:04.527
I'm going to gunnery
school like you are.


1290
01:22:05.097 --> 01:22:06.894
They took you?

1291
01:22:07.332 --> 01:22:08.458
You passed the eye test?

1292
01:22:08.967 --> 01:22:11.492
It's on the bulletin board.

1293
01:22:11.670 --> 01:22:14.161
It was your helping
done it for me.


1294
01:22:14.339 --> 01:22:18.673
-Oh, no, no, no.
-We're gonna be together.


1295
01:22:19.144 --> 01:22:21.544
I've had about all I can take.

1296
01:22:21.713 --> 01:22:24.773
You and him be together,
just leave me out of it.


1297
01:22:24.950 --> 01:22:26.781
-But we're buddies.
-Buddies?


1298
01:22:26.952 --> 01:22:29.420
Last night you said
you was proud of me.


1299
01:22:29.588 --> 01:22:31.647
I was drunk. I didn't
know what I was saying.


1300
01:22:31.823 --> 01:22:35.054
-You give me your watch.
-I was drunk.


1301
01:22:35.861 --> 01:22:39.353
Not when you put me
in charge of the latrine.


1302
01:22:40.465 --> 01:22:44.731
You talk to him. Maybe
you can get through.


1303
01:22:47.205 --> 01:22:49.969
Cleaning the latrine
isn't a good job, Will.


1304
01:22:50.142 --> 01:22:52.269
It's the worst job there is.

1305
01:22:52.444 --> 01:22:53.934
It's a punishment job.

1306
01:22:55.847 --> 01:22:56.905
It is.

1307
01:22:57.082 --> 01:22:59.710
Now do you understand?
There's your buddy.


1308
01:22:59.885 --> 01:23:02.911
Make trouble for
him for a change.


1309
01:23:10.829 --> 01:23:12.387
[SIGHS]

1310
01:23:13.031 --> 01:23:14.362
Great.

1311
01:23:14.533 --> 01:23:18.663
You thought you were gonna miss
him, so you tore up your transfer.


1312
01:23:18.837 --> 01:23:21.897
Well, you don't look
so glad about it now.


1313
01:23:27.446 --> 01:23:29.437
You tore up your transfer, Ben?

1314
01:23:31.483 --> 01:23:33.348
It was just an
application, that's all.


1315
01:23:34.319 --> 01:23:36.583
To the infantry.

1316
01:23:36.755 --> 01:23:38.655
It doesn't make
any difference now.


1317
01:23:38.824 --> 01:23:41.520
After this, I couldn't get
transferred to a troop of mules.


1318
01:23:41.693 --> 01:23:43.058
I didn't know you done that.

1319
01:23:43.228 --> 01:23:46.129
-Just forget about it, will you?
-You ain't sore at me?


1320
01:23:46.298 --> 01:23:48.858
I ain't jumping up and
down, you can say that again.


1321
01:23:49.034 --> 01:23:51.093
You ain't nothing but
trouble since we met...


1322
01:23:51.269 --> 01:23:53.669
...running around acting
like a big, dang donkey.


1323
01:23:54.006 --> 01:23:56.474
I'll make it up to you,
Ben, honest I will.


1324
01:23:57.075 --> 01:24:00.169
Just forget about it, will
you? Don't try to do nothing.


1325
01:24:00.345 --> 01:24:03.405
Oh, we'll still speak because
we'll be in the same outfit...


1326
01:24:03.582 --> 01:24:05.106
...and that's the
military way...


1327
01:24:05.283 --> 01:24:07.581
...but forget about it.
We'll both be better off.


1328
01:24:09.087 --> 01:24:13.217
-Ben, please--
-Gotta go pack for gunnery school.


1329
01:24:18.030 --> 01:24:19.156
Oh, yeah.

1330
01:24:19.331 --> 01:24:23.859
Well, Ben, Sergeant King and me,
we all went to gunnery school together.


1331
01:24:24.036 --> 01:24:25.765
Like The Three Musketeers.

1332
01:24:25.937 --> 01:24:29.134
And they put us on this here
squadron on this here air base?


1333
01:24:29.307 --> 01:24:31.605
And it was way out in
the middle of the country.


1334
01:24:31.777 --> 01:24:33.904
You know, out of the
way of the other outfits.


1335
01:24:34.079 --> 01:24:37.048
And the planes is
what they call obsolete...


1336
01:24:37.215 --> 01:24:41.618
...and the officer crews that run them,
well, they wasn't kept up very much either.


1337
01:24:41.787 --> 01:24:45.348
I guess it's what you might call
a second-line-of-defense outfit.


1338
01:24:45.524 --> 01:24:48.584
But, anyhow, Ben and me was
put on the same flight crew...


1339
01:24:48.760 --> 01:24:51.991
...because they put you according
to how you come in your class...


1340
01:24:52.164 --> 01:24:54.860
...and we was the bottom two.

1341
01:24:55.033 --> 01:24:57.729
Sergeant King though,
he came out on top.


1342
01:24:57.903 --> 01:25:01.339
He did. The instructor said
they never seen nothing like it.


1343
01:25:01.506 --> 01:25:04.703
It was just as if he had copies
of the test before they gave them.


1344
01:25:06.678 --> 01:25:10.739
All right, boys, get this one off
and you can all get back to sleep.


1345
01:25:16.722 --> 01:25:20.920
Hey, look at you with an arm band
and a writing pad and everything.


1346
01:25:21.093 --> 01:25:24.529
All right, get on the plane.
You're taking off right now.


1347
01:25:24.696 --> 01:25:26.823
Hey, we can't.
Everybody ain't here yet.


1348
01:25:26.998 --> 01:25:29.865
The radio operator and the
front gunner, they ain't showed up.


1349
01:25:30.035 --> 01:25:32.469
KING: All right. Get onboard
the plane. Get moving.


1350
01:25:32.637 --> 01:25:34.127
Clear.

1351
01:25:38.710 --> 01:25:41.611
How come we're going
up so early, sergeant?


1352
01:25:41.780 --> 01:25:44.044
To break the sound barrier.

1353
01:25:44.216 --> 01:25:46.912
You gotta sneak up on
it when nobody's looking.


1354
01:25:47.252 --> 01:25:48.913
Oh.

1355
01:26:00.499 --> 01:26:02.831
Excuse me, sir.

1356
01:26:06.738 --> 01:26:09.798
-Excuse me, sirs. Howdy.
-What the--?


1357
01:26:09.975 --> 01:26:12.637
It's all right, George.
He's one of the crew.


1358
01:26:12.811 --> 01:26:14.369
Okay, okay.

1359
01:26:14.546 --> 01:26:16.946
Don't come sneaking up
on people like that, fella.


1360
01:26:17.115 --> 01:26:21.074
Sorry, sir. I just wanted to
see what you all do up here.


1361
01:26:21.253 --> 01:26:23.517
It's on automatic pilot.

1362
01:26:24.990 --> 01:26:28.118
-Did you already let up the wheels?
-Heck, yes.


1363
01:26:28.293 --> 01:26:29.317
Shucks.

1364
01:26:29.494 --> 01:26:33.396
-What are you all do in back, anyhow?
-Nothing much.


1365
01:26:33.565 --> 01:26:37.057
I mostly look out the
blister and sweep up a little.


1366
01:26:39.604 --> 01:26:41.231
Good night.

1367
01:26:45.377 --> 01:26:47.208
Excuse me, sir.

1368
01:26:53.985 --> 01:26:57.216
Take an awful long time
to get to Denver, Colorado.


1369
01:26:57.389 --> 01:26:58.720
What they doing up there?

1370
01:26:58.890 --> 01:27:02.917
Oh, you'd be right proud of them,
Ben. They're working real hard.


1371
01:27:03.094 --> 01:27:05.756
Steering and navigating
and engineering and all.


1372
01:27:07.899 --> 01:27:10.595
Navigator to pilot.
Navigator to pilot, over.


1373
01:27:10.769 --> 01:27:12.327
Pilot to navigator.

1374
01:27:12.504 --> 01:27:15.268
Fred, I wish you wouldn't call
me once we're off the ground.


1375
01:27:15.440 --> 01:27:18.000
We're over the Gulf
of Mexico, you idiot.


1376
01:27:19.344 --> 01:27:21.175
How can we be over
the Gulf of Mexico...


1377
01:27:21.346 --> 01:27:24.008
...when there's a city below
us half the size of New York?


1378
01:27:24.182 --> 01:27:26.173
You wanna come back
here and check the maps?


1379
01:27:26.351 --> 01:27:28.319
I figured our position
by dead reckoning...


1380
01:27:28.486 --> 01:27:31.614
...and we're smack-dab in the
middle of the Gulf of Mexico.


1381
01:27:31.790 --> 01:27:34.759
Hey, fellas, Number

1382
01:27:35.694 --> 01:27:36.820
Okay.

1383
01:27:36.995 --> 01:27:38.394
[ENGINE FALTERING]

1384
01:27:40.398 --> 01:27:43.595
-Prepare for landing.
-This is not a seaplane.


1385
01:27:43.768 --> 01:27:46.601
Copilot to rear gunner.
Copilot to rear gunner. Over.


1386
01:27:46.771 --> 01:27:48.762
[BUZZER SOUNDING]

1387
01:27:55.247 --> 01:27:56.646
Howdy.

1388
01:27:56.815 --> 01:28:00.080
Have you seen anything below
that might have been a body of water?


1389
01:28:00.252 --> 01:28:03.881
No, sir, I ain't seen
nothing. I been sweeping up.


1390
01:28:04.055 --> 01:28:07.252
What is the matter with that radio
operator? Pilot to radio operator.


1391
01:28:07.425 --> 01:28:11.122
-Pilot to radio operator. Over.
-Copilot to radio operator. Over.


1392
01:28:11.296 --> 01:28:16.029
-Navigator to radio operator. Over?
-Rear gunner to everybody.


1393
01:28:16.201 --> 01:28:18.396
Radio operator missed the plane.

1394
01:28:18.837 --> 01:28:20.065
-Oh, no.
-Oh, no.


1395
01:28:20.805 --> 01:28:22.432
-Over.
-Listen, rear gunner...


1396
01:28:22.607 --> 01:28:24.768
...you ought to know
how to operate that radio.


1397
01:28:24.943 --> 01:28:27.969
See if you can find out where
we are. This is an emergency.


1398
01:28:28.146 --> 01:28:31.309
We know exactly where we are.

1399
01:28:31.483 --> 01:28:34.043
Hey, sir, you ought to give
the job to the other gunner.


1400
01:28:34.219 --> 01:28:37.382
I reckon he'd be about the best
dang radio operator there is...


1401
01:28:37.555 --> 01:28:39.614
...in the whole
danged Air Force.


1402
01:28:39.791 --> 01:28:43.955
All right, just put somebody on
that lousy radio! Over and out!


1403
01:28:44.129 --> 01:28:47.565
Hey, hey, hey, Ben. Hey,
listen. Hey, hey, wake up, Ben.


1404
01:28:47.732 --> 01:28:49.893
-What?
-Listen, it's an emergency.


1405
01:28:50.068 --> 01:28:53.799
We're lost and Lieutenant Bridges
wants you to be the radio operator...


1406
01:28:53.972 --> 01:28:55.701
...and find out where we are.

1407
01:28:55.874 --> 01:29:00.174
It's your big chance, Ben, to save
the plane and us and everything.


1408
01:29:00.345 --> 01:29:02.836
-Me?
-They heard what a good soldier you was.


1409
01:29:03.014 --> 01:29:05.949
Golly. Oh, Lord.

1410
01:29:10.121 --> 01:29:13.750
-Hey, here's some instructions.
-Good. Read them off.


1411
01:29:13.925 --> 01:29:16.416
I'll operate and
you be my assistant.


1412
01:29:16.594 --> 01:29:18.255
Assistant?

1413
01:29:18.430 --> 01:29:21.866
Yes, sir. Heh-heh.

1414
01:29:22.167 --> 01:29:24.692
Um.... "Important notice.

1415
01:29:24.869 --> 01:29:28.896
The taxpayers of the
United States paid their--"


1416
01:29:29.074 --> 01:29:33.443
-Here. You operate, I'll read.
-Oh, but they gave the job to you, Ben.


1417
01:29:33.611 --> 01:29:37.069
Go on. I gotta think
for the good of the outfit.


1418
01:29:37.248 --> 01:29:40.740
"Two. Turn oscillator
control knob--"


1419
01:29:40.919 --> 01:29:42.750
I think that's the
big one there.


1420
01:29:42.921 --> 01:29:46.288
"--to transmission
frequency desired."


1421
01:29:47.892 --> 01:29:50.087
Well, what frequency
do we desire?


1422
01:29:50.261 --> 01:29:52.923
Well, I'll leave that up to you.

1423
01:29:53.098 --> 01:29:56.261
Alrighty.

1424
01:29:56.434 --> 01:29:59.335
"Adjust Knob B...

1425
01:29:59.504 --> 01:30:03.770
...so as to obtain
minimum impedance."


1426
01:30:05.610 --> 01:30:09.341
Hey, listen, Ben. We got a
little old radio on the porch...


1427
01:30:09.514 --> 01:30:12.074
...whenever it won't work,
Pa spits in the back of it...


1428
01:30:12.250 --> 01:30:15.651
...and whomps it a good and
it works every time. Let's see.


1429
01:30:23.461 --> 01:30:25.656
There you are, she's a-working.

1430
01:30:25.830 --> 01:30:28.298
-She's a-working.
-We done it, Will.


1431
01:30:28.466 --> 01:30:30.400
Hello?

1432
01:30:30.735 --> 01:30:32.327
[SPITS]

1433
01:30:32.504 --> 01:30:34.267
Hello?

1434
01:30:34.439 --> 01:30:37.772
There. Ha-ha. I told
you I'd find an airport.


1435
01:30:40.945 --> 01:30:43.436
That's a drive-in
movie. Pull up.


1436
01:30:43.615 --> 01:30:46.083
Pull up. Pull up.

1437
01:30:52.524 --> 01:30:53.718
[ENGINE BACKFIRES]

1438
01:30:53.992 --> 01:30:56.017
Hello?

1439
01:30:56.194 --> 01:30:58.628
If you get somebody,
be careful what you say.


1440
01:30:58.797 --> 01:31:02.164
-It might be the enemy.
-What enemy?


1441
01:31:02.333 --> 01:31:06.633
-I don't know, but be careful.
-Okay.


1442
01:31:06.805 --> 01:31:08.773
Hello?

1443
01:31:09.674 --> 01:31:10.971
[SPITS]

1444
01:31:11.142 --> 01:31:12.575
Hello?

1445
01:31:16.181 --> 01:31:18.046
OFFICER: Sergeant.
MAN: I'm clear on one.


1446
01:31:18.216 --> 01:31:19.444
Door.

1447
01:31:19.617 --> 01:31:20.641
[SPITTING OVER RADIO]

1448
01:31:20.819 --> 01:31:24.812
Excuse me, sir, but I'm getting
a very odd signal here. Listen.


1449
01:31:24.989 --> 01:31:28.083
MAN [OVER RADIO]:
--in 5930, chap. Over.


1450
01:31:28.259 --> 01:31:30.022
That is odd.

1451
01:31:30.195 --> 01:31:31.924
Sounds like somebody spitting.

1452
01:31:32.097 --> 01:31:35.464
BEN: Okay, Will, try it
again. WILL: Yes, sir.


1453
01:31:35.633 --> 01:31:37.965
Hello?

1454
01:31:38.136 --> 01:31:40.331
Hello?

1455
01:31:40.505 --> 01:31:42.871
Anybody there?

1456
01:31:43.041 --> 01:31:45.908
-Hello?
-Hello.


1457
01:31:46.077 --> 01:31:48.568
-Hello.
-Hello?


1458
01:31:48.746 --> 01:31:50.805
Howdy.

1459
01:31:50.982 --> 01:31:54.645
-Hey, Ben, I got somebody.
BEN: How about that?


1460
01:31:54.819 --> 01:31:56.946
Who are you? Where are you?

1461
01:31:57.122 --> 01:31:59.056
WILL: Ben, he wants
to know who we are.


1462
01:31:59.224 --> 01:32:01.692
Answer me. Who
the devil are you?


1463
01:32:01.860 --> 01:32:04.795
He talks like an American, Ben.

1464
01:32:05.530 --> 01:32:08.021
Ben says, "First, who are you?"

1465
01:32:08.199 --> 01:32:10.759
This is command post
Operation Prometheus.


1466
01:32:10.935 --> 01:32:13.563
-Are you in an airplane?
-Sure are.


1467
01:32:13.738 --> 01:32:17.230
-Oh, great Scott.
-No, sir. Stockdale.


1468
01:32:17.408 --> 01:32:19.399
That must be this
pip on the scope, sir.


1469
01:32:19.577 --> 01:32:22.239
-Heading straight towards the tower, sir.
-Judas priest.


1470
01:32:22.413 --> 01:32:25.473
-Is this the Gulf of Mexico?
-No, you idiot.


1471
01:32:25.650 --> 01:32:29.279
-Send word to stop the detonator.
-It's too late, sir. Zero-minus-4.


1472
01:32:29.454 --> 01:32:31.479
Hey, where'd you say we was?

1473
01:32:31.656 --> 01:32:34.648
You're right over Yucca Flats,
Nevada. The atomic proving ground.


1474
01:32:34.826 --> 01:32:37.386
Listen to me. I want you
to turn that plane around...


1475
01:32:37.562 --> 01:32:39.530
...and head right back
where you came from.


1476
01:32:39.697 --> 01:32:41.756
There they are.
Straight toward the tower.


1477
01:32:41.933 --> 01:32:45.266
Ben says, "Sorry. Our orders
come from General Bush.


1478
01:32:45.436 --> 01:32:46.835
We got to do like he says. "

1479
01:32:47.005 --> 01:32:50.873
-Eugene Bush?
-Our commanding general.


1480
01:32:51.042 --> 01:32:54.034
-Fat fellow with a mustache.
-I might've known.


1481
01:32:54.212 --> 01:32:55.975
Get me through to General Bush.

1482
01:32:56.147 --> 01:32:57.944
That idiot, I'll
kill him for this.


1483
01:32:58.116 --> 01:33:00.311
Get me General Bush,

1484
01:33:00.485 --> 01:33:03.386
All right. I don't care what Ben
says or what Eugene Bush said.


1485
01:33:03.555 --> 01:33:06.023
I'm a general too, in
the U.S. Army infantry.


1486
01:33:06.191 --> 01:33:07.488
The infantry?

1487
01:33:07.659 --> 01:33:10.594
Yes, and I'm ordering you to
turn that plane around this minute.


1488
01:33:10.762 --> 01:33:12.059
You're heading straight into--

1489
01:33:12.230 --> 01:33:15.461
[STATIC WHINING OVER RADIO]

1490
01:33:15.633 --> 01:33:18.193
Hello? Hello?

1491
01:33:18.369 --> 01:33:21.805
-Great Scott, I've lost them.
-He's right here, sir.


1492
01:33:24.342 --> 01:33:25.434
Bush here.

1493
01:33:25.610 --> 01:33:27.942
Eugene, this is Vernon Pollard.

1494
01:33:28.546 --> 01:33:33.210
Vernon. Well, how
are you, old boy?


1495
01:33:33.384 --> 01:33:35.477
You've sabotaged
my operation, you idiot.


1496
01:33:35.653 --> 01:33:38.918
You were ordered to send your plane
far away and one is coming over us.


1497
01:33:39.090 --> 01:33:41.285
I sent them away, Vernon.

1498
01:33:41.459 --> 01:33:44.485
-I sent them to Denver.
-I don't care where you sent them.


1499
01:33:44.662 --> 01:33:47.222
-What's wrong with your communications?
-What's wrong...


1500
01:33:47.398 --> 01:33:49.958
...with your security
measures, old boy?


1501
01:33:50.134 --> 01:33:51.158
Shut up and listen.

1502
01:33:51.336 --> 01:33:53.236
I'm trying to reestablish
radio contact.


1503
01:33:53.404 --> 01:33:55.998
What kind of idiot radio
operators do you put in planes?


1504
01:33:56.174 --> 01:34:00.406
What kind of idiot radio operators
did you put in those planes?


1505
01:34:00.578 --> 01:34:01.875
I'll skin you for this, Eugene.

1506
01:34:02.046 --> 01:34:03.513
[SPITTING OVER RADIO]

1507
01:34:03.681 --> 01:34:05.171
Sir, I've got that signal again.

1508
01:34:08.219 --> 01:34:10.278
WILL: Hello? MAN:
Twenty-three, stand by.


1509
01:34:10.455 --> 01:34:13.117
Hello?

1510
01:34:13.291 --> 01:34:17.159
Hello, listen, here's
your General Bush.


1511
01:34:17.328 --> 01:34:19.421
They got General
Bush there, Ben.


1512
01:34:19.597 --> 01:34:22.225
Eugene, I'm putting the
telephone next to the microphone.


1513
01:34:22.400 --> 01:34:23.833
Tell this idiot to turn back.

1514
01:34:24.002 --> 01:34:26.835
Hello? Who is this?

1515
01:34:27.005 --> 01:34:30.304
-Private Stockdale, sir.
-This is General Bush, Stockdale.


1516
01:34:30.475 --> 01:34:33.467
-Stockdale?
-Don't move, King.


1517
01:34:33.645 --> 01:34:35.977
Tell your pilot to reverse
course immediately.


1518
01:34:36.147 --> 01:34:40.379
-You're in extreme danger.
-Roger, sir. Wilco.


1519
01:34:40.551 --> 01:34:43.384
Ben says, "How do we
know you are General Bush?"


1520
01:34:43.554 --> 01:34:45.784
Tell him Sergeant King
will give him his watch.


1521
01:34:45.957 --> 01:34:49.051
-What? Huh?
-It's the only way, sir.


1522
01:34:49.227 --> 01:34:51.627
Sergeant King
will give his watch.


1523
01:34:51.796 --> 01:34:54.959
-He will?
-I think so.


1524
01:34:55.133 --> 01:34:58.296
That's good enough for me.
I'll go tell Lieutenant Bridges.


1525
01:34:58.469 --> 01:35:01.029
I'll tell him this personal.

1526
01:35:06.010 --> 01:35:08.638
Excuse me, lieutenant, but
we talked with General Bush...


1527
01:35:08.813 --> 01:35:10.576
...and he says
we're in real danger...


1528
01:35:10.748 --> 01:35:13.012
...and you should reverse
course quick as a wink.


1529
01:35:13.184 --> 01:35:16.483
-Danger? Where are we?
-Smack-dab over Yucca Flats, Nevada.


1530
01:35:16.654 --> 01:35:18.645
Holy Pete.

1531
01:35:20.024 --> 01:35:23.118
Hey, I just wanted to tell you
what a good job Ben done.


1532
01:35:23.294 --> 01:35:25.990
Maybe you could recommend
him for a promotion or something.


1533
01:35:26.164 --> 01:35:28.530
-Shut up. Don't bother me.
-But, lieutenant...


1534
01:35:28.700 --> 01:35:30.895
...maybe you could get
him a medal or something.


1535
01:35:31.069 --> 01:35:33.503
Get back to your
station! Don't bother me!


1536
01:35:33.671 --> 01:35:37.004
Don't bother me again for
anything! That's an order!


1537
01:35:39.711 --> 01:35:41.406
Yes, sir.

1538
01:35:42.780 --> 01:35:44.247
Twenty seconds, sir.

1539
01:35:44.415 --> 01:35:46.349
It's working, sir.
They're turning.


1540
01:35:46.517 --> 01:35:48.610
You did it, Eugene.
They're turning.


1541
01:35:48.786 --> 01:35:50.720
There they go.
They're still turning.


1542
01:35:50.888 --> 01:35:53.413
No. They're heading
for the tower again.


1543
01:35:53.591 --> 01:35:55.684
Ten seconds, sir.

1544
01:35:55.860 --> 01:35:57.760
It's all your fault, Eugene.

1545
01:35:57.929 --> 01:36:00.921
You've never forgiven me for
those hazings back at the point.


1546
01:36:01.866 --> 01:36:04.300
It's all your fault,
you blundering idiot.


1547
01:36:04.469 --> 01:36:07.131
-For 30 years you've been out to
get me. LIEUTENANT: Five, four--


1548
01:36:07.305 --> 01:36:12.368
-And now you're out to wreck my career.
--three, two, one, zero.


1549
01:36:20.184 --> 01:36:23.244
What happened? 
What happened?

1550
01:36:24.088 --> 01:36:26.886
-Look, we're on fire!
-We got to jump out!


1551
01:36:27.058 --> 01:36:28.355
I got to tell them up front!

1552
01:36:28.526 --> 01:36:31.427
No, they said they didn't want
to be bothered about anything...


1553
01:36:31.596 --> 01:36:33.928
-...no matter what!
-But we can't leave like that!


1554
01:36:34.098 --> 01:36:36.362
-They said it was an order, Ben!
-No, Will!


1555
01:36:36.534 --> 01:36:38.729
WILL: Hang on!

1556
01:36:38.903 --> 01:36:41.303
[SCREAMS]

1557
01:36:47.678 --> 01:36:49.168
Pull to the left!

1558
01:36:49.347 --> 01:36:52.748
No, pull to the right!

1559
01:36:52.917 --> 01:36:54.942
Hold still, Ben.

1560
01:36:55.119 --> 01:36:56.643
What'd you do it for?

1561
01:36:56.821 --> 01:36:59.722
You snatched me right out of
the plane! What'd you do it for?


1562
01:36:59.891 --> 01:37:03.327
Well, I know you didn't have
time to put on your parachute.


1563
01:37:03.494 --> 01:37:05.587
And heck, you'd have
done the same for me.


1564
01:37:05.763 --> 01:37:06.787
No, I wouldn't.

1565
01:37:06.964 --> 01:37:10.764
Our post was the tail of the
plane and nobody told us to quit it.


1566
01:37:10.935 --> 01:37:13.904
But the tail was on fire, Ben.

1567
01:37:14.071 --> 01:37:16.232
Our post was a-quitting us.

1568
01:37:16.407 --> 01:37:18.534
Do you know what we are now?

1569
01:37:18.709 --> 01:37:21.109
-Well, we're alive.
-We're deserters.


1570
01:37:21.279 --> 01:37:23.577
Deserters!

1571
01:37:23.748 --> 01:37:26.842
Quit wiggling, Ben. Please.

1572
01:37:27.018 --> 01:37:31.250
The first lick of danger and
you snatch me away from it.


1573
01:37:31.422 --> 01:37:35.256
I'd rather be a dead
hero than a live deserter.


1574
01:37:35.426 --> 01:37:38.987
I ain't gonna drop you
no matter what you say.


1575
01:37:40.965 --> 01:37:42.956
[MARCHING BAND PLAYING]

1576
01:37:44.635 --> 01:37:47.103
Hey, we can slip through
here and nobody'll see us.


1577
01:37:47.271 --> 01:37:51.105
We're in for it and we ought to report
back through the gate. That's military.


1578
01:37:51.275 --> 01:37:53.971
Yeah, and have them grab us
before we get to the general?


1579
01:37:54.145 --> 01:37:57.808
No, by dog, we'll report to General
Bush's office and explain to him in person.


1580
01:37:57.982 --> 01:37:59.916
It'll be all right,
Ben, you'll see.


1581
01:38:00.918 --> 01:38:03.978
Everything seems happy. Sounds
like they're having a band concert.


1582
01:38:04.155 --> 01:38:05.452
Oh, Will.

1583
01:38:05.623 --> 01:38:08.319
It'll be all right, Ben, they'll
give us some new uniforms.


1584
01:38:08.493 --> 01:38:09.960
Yeah, with numbers on the back.

1585
01:38:10.528 --> 01:38:13.759
Let's see. Bush's office
is on the other side.


1586
01:38:13.931 --> 01:38:18.391
We'll just slip along cautious-like
and keep cover along the buildings.


1587
01:38:29.313 --> 01:38:32.646
WILL: How about that? It's
some kind of real big ceremony.


1588
01:38:32.817 --> 01:38:35.377
BEN: Look, the
flag, it's at half-mast.


1589
01:38:35.553 --> 01:38:38.181
It's a funeral ceremony,
that's what it is.


1590
01:38:38.356 --> 01:38:41.985
Lieutenant Brides and them
others, they didn't get out of the plane.


1591
01:38:42.159 --> 01:38:43.888
Now we got that
on our heads too.


1592
01:38:44.061 --> 01:38:49.590
Oh, now, Ben, they wasn't so easygoing
they wouldn't know they was on fire.


1593
01:38:49.767 --> 01:38:52.099
We'll find out when
we report to the general.


1594
01:38:52.270 --> 01:38:56.400
-Everything'll come out real dandy.
-Yeah, sure.


1595
01:38:58.876 --> 01:39:02.607
Ten days ago, in
Operation Prometheus...


1596
01:39:02.780 --> 01:39:05.578
...the power of the atom
bomb was challenged...


1597
01:39:05.750 --> 01:39:08.810
...by a band of
battle-hardened air aces.


1598
01:39:08.986 --> 01:39:12.547
Well, brush, man, brush.
That's genuine leather.


1599
01:39:12.723 --> 01:39:15.817
-Here, watch that sleeve.
-The grandstands are full, sir.


1600
01:39:15.993 --> 01:39:17.620
You're darned right they are.

1601
01:39:17.795 --> 01:39:20.491
Those men are on duty. All
leaves were canceled today.


1602
01:39:20.665 --> 01:39:23.896
Senator Hawk and Senator Winkle
have come out of the reviewing stand.


1603
01:39:24.068 --> 01:39:27.060
-Good. Good. My car here, Baker?
-I'm certain it is. I'll check.


1604
01:39:27.238 --> 01:39:30.969
Abel, check and see if those idiot
officers are on hand to be decorated.


1605
01:39:31.142 --> 01:39:32.632
Yes, sir.

1606
01:39:37.615 --> 01:39:40.982
Two did not return.

1607
01:39:41.152 --> 01:39:44.610
Two did not return.

1608
01:39:45.556 --> 01:39:48.423
In the shattered
tail of the plane...


1609
01:39:48.593 --> 01:39:53.292
...all that remained were
two charred flight helmets...


1610
01:39:53.464 --> 01:39:56.865
...and a handful of dust.

1611
01:39:58.436 --> 01:40:00.131
Excuse me, sir, l--

1612
01:40:01.105 --> 01:40:03.801
What the devil are
you men doing here?


1613
01:40:04.241 --> 01:40:06.471
Well, you see, sir, we come to--

1614
01:40:06.644 --> 01:40:09.374
Your uniform is filthy, boy.

1615
01:40:09.547 --> 01:40:12.948
I know, sir. We hitchhiked some,
but we had to walk a lot and--


1616
01:40:13.117 --> 01:40:15.312
People are coming
from miles around.


1617
01:40:15.486 --> 01:40:19.684
Generals, senators to do
homage to two enlisted men.


1618
01:40:19.857 --> 01:40:21.722
Your brothers-in-arms.

1619
01:40:21.892 --> 01:40:24.486
And you don't even have
enough courtesy and respect...


1620
01:40:24.662 --> 01:40:26.527
...to put on a decent uniform.

1621
01:40:26.697 --> 01:40:29.860
-Sir, please, I'd like to turn myself in.
-He didn't jump, sir.


1622
01:40:30.034 --> 01:40:31.331
I pulled him out.

1623
01:40:32.370 --> 01:40:34.270
The car is ready, sir.

1624
01:40:34.538 --> 01:40:36.699
What squadron are you men in?

1625
01:40:36.874 --> 01:40:39.468
-The ninth squadron, sir.
-The ninth?


1626
01:40:39.644 --> 01:40:42.306
Stackpole and
Whitehead's own outfit.


1627
01:40:42.480 --> 01:40:45.472
-Stockdale and Whitledge, sir.
-Stockdale and Whitledge, sir.


1628
01:40:46.384 --> 01:40:48.909
Well, whoever they were.

1629
01:40:49.086 --> 01:40:52.021
Now, you two are going right
back into that conference room...


1630
01:40:52.189 --> 01:40:54.248
...until I finish this ceremony.

1631
01:40:54.425 --> 01:40:57.758
And then we'll see if we
can put a little decency...


1632
01:40:57.928 --> 01:41:01.329
...and esprit de corps into you.

1633
01:41:01.499 --> 01:41:05.993
Dirty uniforms.
Today of all days.


1634
01:41:06.203 --> 01:41:08.831
Well, you men heard
the orders. Get in there.


1635
01:41:13.411 --> 01:41:16.710
Well, we turned
ourselves in, I think.


1636
01:41:16.881 --> 01:41:20.749
Yeah, wait until he finds out that besides
wearing dirty uniforms, we're deserters.


1637
01:41:20.918 --> 01:41:22.909
[WHISTLING]

1638
01:41:30.895 --> 01:41:32.886
[MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

1639
01:41:45.810 --> 01:41:46.970
Ah-ah.

1640
01:41:47.144 --> 01:41:48.168
What's the matter?

1641
01:41:48.345 --> 01:41:50.472
Lieutenant Bridges
on the back cover.


1642
01:41:51.515 --> 01:41:54.609
I wished you would look.

1643
01:41:54.785 --> 01:41:56.616
[DRUMROLL PLAYS OVER PA]

1644
01:41:56.787 --> 01:42:00.154
MAN [OVER PA]: General Bush has just
taken his place on the reviewing stand...


1645
01:42:00.324 --> 01:42:03.191
...and now the four lieutenants
who braved the atomic blast...


1646
01:42:03.360 --> 01:42:06.727
...and will receive the Air Medal,
are bravely mounting the platform.


1647
01:42:06.897 --> 01:42:11.163
The lieutenants. They're alive.
They're getting medals. They're heroes.


1648
01:42:11.335 --> 01:42:12.359
Golly.

1649
01:42:12.536 --> 01:42:14.868
If we'd have stayed on,
we'd have been heroes.


1650
01:42:15.039 --> 01:42:17.234
It is a solemn moment,
ladies and gentlemen.


1651
01:42:17.408 --> 01:42:20.172
The many visiting dignitaries
standing at attention...


1652
01:42:20.344 --> 01:42:23.404
...the flag at half-mast
in honor of the two men...


1653
01:42:23.581 --> 01:42:26.744
...who gave their lives in
Operation Prometheus...


1654
01:42:26.917 --> 01:42:29.351
...Privates Stockdale
and Whitledge.


1655
01:42:31.455 --> 01:42:33.787
-Stockdale and Whitledge?
-Stockdale and Whitledge?


1656
01:42:33.958 --> 01:42:36.791
Yes, Stockdale and Whitledge.

1657
01:42:36.961 --> 01:42:40.761
Names that will live
as long as men are free.


1658
01:42:40.931 --> 01:42:43.491
We are heroes, Ben.

1659
01:42:43.667 --> 01:42:45.032
But we ain't dead.

1660
01:42:45.202 --> 01:42:47.261
Well, that makes it
even better, don't it?


1661
01:42:47.438 --> 01:42:52.102
They think we're heroes and we're a
couple of rotten, no-good deserters.


1662
01:42:52.576 --> 01:42:54.476
[LAUGHS]

1663
01:42:54.645 --> 01:42:59.014
Golly, will they be surprised.

1664
01:42:59.183 --> 01:43:02.084
They'll kill us, that's what
they'll do. They'll kill us.


1665
01:43:12.496 --> 01:43:14.623
Hi.

1666
01:43:20.905 --> 01:43:22.896
[MUTTERING]

1667
01:43:23.874 --> 01:43:25.705
You've gone crazy.

1668
01:43:25.876 --> 01:43:27.810
Seeing things.

1669
01:43:35.586 --> 01:43:36.610
Howdy, sergeant.

1670
01:43:36.787 --> 01:43:39.915
Private Whitledge reporting for
duty after an unforeseen delay, sir.


1671
01:43:40.090 --> 01:43:44.550
I bet you never expected to
see us again, but here we are.


1672
01:43:44.795 --> 01:43:47.161
No, no, no.

1673
01:43:47.331 --> 01:43:50.300
Didn't I tell you he'd
be surprised, Ben?


1674
01:43:51.969 --> 01:43:56.099
-Why ain't you dead?
-No excuse, sir.


1675
01:43:56.607 --> 01:44:01.135
-You ain't dead. You ain't dead.
-Well, see, I had my parachute on.


1676
01:44:01.312 --> 01:44:04.907
I was the one who
identified your remains.


1677
01:44:05.082 --> 01:44:08.609
Two charred helmets
and a handful of dust.


1678
01:44:09.453 --> 01:44:12.286
-They're having a big ceremony down there.
-Yeah.


1679
01:44:12.456 --> 01:44:17.325
BUSH: Ten days ago, in
Operation Prometheus...


1680
01:44:17.494 --> 01:44:20.930
...the power of the atom
bomb was challenged....


1681
01:44:21.098 --> 01:44:22.793
-Is that the general?
-The general.


1682
01:44:22.967 --> 01:44:25.663
-Is he giving us medals?
-Medals.


1683
01:44:25.836 --> 01:44:27.736
-Now, there you go, Ben.
-General. Medals.


1684
01:44:27.905 --> 01:44:29.202
Now, get back in that room.

1685
01:44:29.373 --> 01:44:32.001
-Hey, that's no way to act, sergeant.
-Just get in there.


1686
01:44:32.176 --> 01:44:33.905
Ben and me is alive and you--

1687
01:44:34.078 --> 01:44:35.102
Stay where you are.

1688
01:44:35.279 --> 01:44:38.646
Oh, I don't deserve
this, I don't deserve....


1689
01:44:39.216 --> 01:44:42.083
Captain. Captain. Captain!

1690
01:44:42.253 --> 01:44:43.277
We'll be shot.

1691
01:44:43.454 --> 01:44:46.287
No, it's just he's kind
of surprised right now.


1692
01:44:46.457 --> 01:44:50.052
Later on they'll all be
glad we're here. You'll see.


1693
01:44:50.227 --> 01:44:55.062
Sergeant, will you--? Will
you--? What's the matter? Sar--


1694
01:44:55.232 --> 01:44:57.393
Are you nuts?

1695
01:45:02.840 --> 01:45:04.102
No.

1696
01:45:04.275 --> 01:45:05.401
Oh....

1697
01:45:05.576 --> 01:45:09.342
Don't move, you
understand? Just don't move.


1698
01:45:13.217 --> 01:45:15.447
Don't move or
I'll have you shot!


1699
01:45:23.260 --> 01:45:25.820
You, get over to that
reviewing stand on the double.


1700
01:45:25.996 --> 01:45:27.725
Tell the general to
stop proceedings.


1701
01:45:27.898 --> 01:45:30.332
There's radio, television
and newsreel cameras there.


1702
01:45:30.501 --> 01:45:33.868
If he gives out posthumous medals
to two men who are in his own office...


1703
01:45:34.038 --> 01:45:37.337
...he'll be the laughing
stock of the whole country.


1704
01:45:37.508 --> 01:45:39.476
Step on it!

1705
01:45:43.414 --> 01:45:45.473
Stay away from those
windows, you understand?


1706
01:45:45.649 --> 01:45:47.446
Stay away from those doors.

1707
01:45:47.618 --> 01:45:50.086
And if anybody comes in
here, you tell them you're....


1708
01:45:50.254 --> 01:45:52.347
John Jones and Jack
Smith. You got that?


1709
01:45:52.856 --> 01:45:54.016
Yes, sir.

1710
01:45:56.961 --> 01:45:58.929
They're gonna kill us.

1711
01:45:59.663 --> 01:46:03.861
-They're gonna kill us.
-No, they ain't.


1712
01:46:04.668 --> 01:46:06.363
Breathe deep.

1713
01:46:07.404 --> 01:46:08.428
What's going on here?

1714
01:46:08.605 --> 01:46:11.768
Sergeant King just jumped an air
policeman and stole his motorcycle.


1715
01:46:11.942 --> 01:46:15.844
The two men who are getting the
posthumous medals, they're inside.


1716
01:46:16.013 --> 01:46:19.244
-The medals?
-No, the men.


1717
01:46:19.516 --> 01:46:23.577
-You're drunk.
-Go ahead. Look.


1718
01:46:28.525 --> 01:46:30.720
-Who are you?
-I'm John Jones...


1719
01:46:30.894 --> 01:46:33.055
...and this here is Jack Smith.

1720
01:46:35.499 --> 01:46:38.366
Jim, if you're trying to be
comical, it'll be the last time...


1721
01:46:38.535 --> 01:46:42.403
...because jokes about the
dead is carrying it a little bit too far.


1722
01:46:45.275 --> 01:46:46.742
Well, did you stop him in time?

1723
01:46:46.910 --> 01:46:51.847
Sir, I informed him of the situation and
advised him that contrary to intelligence--


1724
01:46:52.016 --> 01:46:54.109
In English, you idiot.

1725
01:46:54.284 --> 01:46:57.776
Had he presented the
medals or had he not?


1726
01:46:57.955 --> 01:46:58.979
Yes, sir, he had, sir.

1727
01:46:59.156 --> 01:47:01.454
-Holy.
-Well, what did he say?


1728
01:47:01.625 --> 01:47:03.684
Well, sir, he said--

1729
01:47:03.861 --> 01:47:08.264
BUSH: I'll court-martial everybody
in the whole damned Air Force.


1730
01:47:08.432 --> 01:47:10.900
That's what he said, sir.

1731
01:47:12.202 --> 01:47:15.399
Where are they? 
Where are they?

1732
01:47:15.572 --> 01:47:20.271
Where are those two privates who
hold my career in the palm of their hands?


1733
01:47:20.444 --> 01:47:22.309
In there, sir.

1734
01:47:32.423 --> 01:47:34.448
You two.

1735
01:47:34.625 --> 01:47:36.115
Yes, sir.

1736
01:47:36.293 --> 01:47:38.386
We got back as
quick as we could.


1737
01:47:38.562 --> 01:47:41.963
And I sure do appreciate
you giving us medals and all...


1738
01:47:42.132 --> 01:47:44.896
...and setting the
flags at half-mast.


1739
01:47:46.136 --> 01:47:48.604
Well, I got the whole
thing figured out too, sir.


1740
01:47:49.973 --> 01:47:53.136
Well, you know that handful of dust
Sergeant King was talking about?


1741
01:47:54.945 --> 01:47:58.540
Well, that's all it was.
A handful of dust. Heh.


1742
01:48:00.050 --> 01:48:04.316
If I'd had known you all was gonna think
it was us, I'd have swept it under a seat.


1743
01:48:04.488 --> 01:48:08.925
But, anyhow, what it comes
down to is we ain't dead.


1744
01:48:09.560 --> 01:48:14.896
[MUTTERING]

1745
01:48:18.902 --> 01:48:24.101
Ten minutes ago, in front of half the
brass in the continental United States...


1746
01:48:24.274 --> 01:48:29.075
...I awarded the Air Medal
to a handful of sweepings.


1747
01:48:29.246 --> 01:48:32.682
Do you know what this is gonna
do to me when this story gets out?


1748
01:48:32.850 --> 01:48:34.147
Sir, I didn't know.

1749
01:48:34.318 --> 01:48:39.051
Tomorrow I will probably be known
throughout the entire Pentagon...


1750
01:48:39.223 --> 01:48:41.885
...as old Dustpan.

1751
01:48:45.696 --> 01:48:48.164
I've got to get those
two men off my base.


1752
01:48:48.332 --> 01:48:50.493
If anybody sees them,
if anybody hears them--


1753
01:48:50.667 --> 01:48:53.261
Sir, couldn't you transfer
them to another base?


1754
01:48:53.437 --> 01:48:56.304
Shut up. What?

1755
01:48:56.473 --> 01:48:59.203
Oh. Oh.

1756
01:49:00.377 --> 01:49:02.311
Yes.

1757
01:49:03.547 --> 01:49:07.415
You go over to S-1 and
get as many DD-613 forms...


1758
01:49:07.584 --> 01:49:09.575
-...as you can lay your hands on.
-Yes, sir.


1759
01:49:09.753 --> 01:49:12.722
You, go out and get another
car and bring it around back.


1760
01:49:12.890 --> 01:49:14.790
-Quietly.
-Yes, sir.


1761
01:49:14.958 --> 01:49:18.985
Get a command car and
put the curtains up all around.


1762
01:49:21.665 --> 01:49:24.190
WILL: Well, they put us
in this here command car...


1763
01:49:24.368 --> 01:49:27.531
...and took us way out here
in the woods, real secret like...


1764
01:49:27.704 --> 01:49:30.434
...with all kinds of guards
around us and everything.


1765
01:49:32.409 --> 01:49:34.900
You know what to do.
Challenge everybody.


1766
01:49:35.078 --> 01:49:37.376
The password is: Nightmare.

1767
01:49:37.548 --> 01:49:39.106
Nightmare.

1768
01:49:39.283 --> 01:49:42.309
If anybody fails
to give it, shoot.


1769
01:49:42.486 --> 01:49:45.353
Okay, sentries, take
your posts on the double.


1770
01:49:51.828 --> 01:49:54.456
Are you sure we've got
the whole area surrounded?


1771
01:49:54.631 --> 01:49:57.464
I think so, sir. I've never
done anything like this before.


1772
01:49:57.634 --> 01:49:59.363
Well, do you think I have?

1773
01:49:59.536 --> 01:50:03.438
General, it sure is exciting,
ain't it? Where's Ben?


1774
01:50:03.607 --> 01:50:10.069
Look, you just stand right over
there and let me handle this, please.


1775
01:50:10.247 --> 01:50:13.910
What the devil is keeping General Pollard?
Are the forms ready for him to sign?


1776
01:50:14.084 --> 01:50:15.449
Corporal's working on them, sir.

1777
01:50:15.619 --> 01:50:16.711
[CAR APPROACHING]

1778
01:50:19.289 --> 01:50:21.257
-That must be Pollard's car now.
-Yes, sir.


1779
01:50:21.425 --> 01:50:23.484
-Speed him up.
-Yes, sir.


1780
01:50:23.994 --> 01:50:26.428
SENTRY: Halt. Advance
and give the password.


1781
01:50:26.597 --> 01:50:27.962
[GUNSHOTS]

1782
01:50:28.298 --> 01:50:30.266
Great Scott,
they've shot Pollard.


1783
01:50:30.434 --> 01:50:34.063
POLLARD: Stop. Stop. Eugene,
tell these idiots to stop shooting.


1784
01:50:34.238 --> 01:50:35.967
It's me. Vernon.

1785
01:50:36.139 --> 01:50:37.163
[GUNSHOT]

1786
01:50:37.341 --> 01:50:38.672
Give the password.

1787
01:50:38.842 --> 01:50:41.276
POLLARD: I've forgotten
the damned thing.


1788
01:50:41.445 --> 01:50:42.469
Nightmare.

1789
01:50:43.046 --> 01:50:45.344
Nightmare!

1790
01:50:45.515 --> 01:50:46.539
[GUNSHOT]

1791
01:50:46.750 --> 01:50:49.014
POLLARD: Nightmare, you stupid--

1792
01:50:49.186 --> 01:50:50.813
Come back here, you.

1793
01:50:52.990 --> 01:50:55.925
Look, here, Eugene, you're
carrying this thing a little too far.


1794
01:50:56.093 --> 01:50:58.288
I'm sorry, Vernon, the
sentries are nervous.


1795
01:50:58.462 --> 01:50:59.486
No reason for that.

1796
01:50:59.663 --> 01:51:00.687
[LOUD POUNDING]

1797
01:51:00.864 --> 01:51:02.092
-Nightmare!
-Nightmare!


1798
01:51:03.400 --> 01:51:04.924
What's that?

1799
01:51:05.636 --> 01:51:09.037
I'm sorry, Vernon, it's
the other dead hero.


1800
01:51:09.206 --> 01:51:10.298
The talkative one.

1801
01:51:10.474 --> 01:51:12.874
I put him in the
trunk for total security.


1802
01:51:13.043 --> 01:51:16.274
Ben's in the trunk?
How about that?


1803
01:51:16.446 --> 01:51:19.176
-Get him out, Stockdale.
-Yes, sir.


1804
01:51:20.417 --> 01:51:23.853
Listen, Eugene, they could lower
the boom on us, pulling a deal like this.


1805
01:51:24.021 --> 01:51:25.921
We are in trouble, Vernon.

1806
01:51:26.089 --> 01:51:27.647
Clear up to our pensions.

1807
01:51:27.824 --> 01:51:30.452
Now, come on and
sign those papers.


1808
01:51:34.131 --> 01:51:36.031
Howdy, Ben.

1809
01:51:37.401 --> 01:51:39.335
Oh....

1810
01:51:39.503 --> 01:51:42.472
I knew it. I knew it.

1811
01:51:42.639 --> 01:51:45.267
They got us out in the
middle of no man's land.


1812
01:51:45.442 --> 01:51:48.605
Oh, I don't know. I
think it's kind of pleasant.


1813
01:51:48.779 --> 01:51:50.440
Goodbye, Will.

1814
01:51:50.614 --> 01:51:53.879
-We just got here, Ben.
-And we ain't never going back.


1815
01:51:54.051 --> 01:51:57.384
Will, I know you didn't
do it on purpose...


1816
01:51:57.554 --> 01:52:00.182
...and I know there wasn't
no meanness behind it.


1817
01:52:01.425 --> 01:52:03.222
I forgive you.

1818
01:52:04.127 --> 01:52:07.858
-Then we're buddies again?
-For a little while.


1819
01:52:08.031 --> 01:52:09.658
All right, Whitledge, you first.

1820
01:52:09.833 --> 01:52:14.167
Sentry, take him in there, have
him sign everything in triplicate.


1821
01:52:16.239 --> 01:52:19.572
-Bye, Will.
-Bye, Ben.


1822
01:52:19.743 --> 01:52:23.839
Golly, is he gonna be surprised.

1823
01:52:26.883 --> 01:52:31.786
You know, everybody's all the time
saying how sergeants is mean and tough.


1824
01:52:31.955 --> 01:52:36.585
So I'm right glad you was my first
one because you showed me different.


1825
01:52:36.760 --> 01:52:38.523
Why, thank you, Will.

1826
01:52:40.564 --> 01:52:43.055
All right, Will, I'm gonna
give you the watch anyway.


1827
01:52:43.233 --> 01:52:47.727
-Oh, gee, I never held that against you.
-Oh, go on and take it.


1828
01:52:47.904 --> 01:52:50.498
My mother would be
glad for you to have it.


1829
01:52:50.674 --> 01:52:51.936
We're square now.

1830
01:52:52.109 --> 01:52:54.543
I don't owe you nothing and
you don't owe me nothing.


1831
01:52:54.711 --> 01:52:56.406
We're square.

1832
01:52:57.514 --> 01:52:58.538
-King?
-Yeah.


1833
01:52:58.715 --> 01:53:00.683
What's the matter
with that Whitledge?


1834
01:53:00.851 --> 01:53:06.653
He keeps saying he's sorry he has
only one life to give for his country.


1835
01:53:08.291 --> 01:53:10.919
He figures you brought
us out here to get shot.


1836
01:53:11.595 --> 01:53:13.187
-Shot?
-Shot.


1837
01:53:15.165 --> 01:53:17.463
Ridiculous.

1838
01:53:17.701 --> 01:53:19.896
All these witnesses, Vernon.

1839
01:53:20.070 --> 01:53:22.038
Take a smoke. Ahem.

1840
01:53:22.205 --> 01:53:25.766
All right, Stockdale, I just have a
couple of letters for you to sign...


1841
01:53:25.942 --> 01:53:28.206
...and then we'll be through
with this whole mess.


1842
01:53:28.378 --> 01:53:30.369
This one's to your folks...

1843
01:53:30.547 --> 01:53:35.541
...saying that you're on a
very important secret mission.


1844
01:53:35.719 --> 01:53:39.883
This one certifies you've never
heard of Operation Prometheus...


1845
01:53:40.056 --> 01:53:43.719
...and have never been on
my base in your entire life.


1846
01:53:43.894 --> 01:53:46.055
Sign here.

1847
01:53:49.533 --> 01:53:52.991
But, if we never heard of
Operation What You Call It...


1848
01:53:53.170 --> 01:53:55.832
-...we don't get no medals, do we?
-Medals? Of course not.


1849
01:53:56.006 --> 01:53:57.030
Sign here.

1850
01:53:57.207 --> 01:54:00.267
Ben, he sets a whole lot of stock
in medals and things like that.


1851
01:54:00.544 --> 01:54:04.878
You want me to present a medal out
in the woods in the middle of the night?


1852
01:54:05.048 --> 01:54:06.140
That's right.

1853
01:54:06.316 --> 01:54:10.685
Hey, we can get everybody standing up all
around and turn one of the cars around...


1854
01:54:10.854 --> 01:54:12.788
...so the lights are shining.

1855
01:54:12.956 --> 01:54:16.585
-Hey, maybe get a little music on the radio.
-No, no. I don't have any medals.


1856
01:54:16.760 --> 01:54:19.160
WILL: Hey, driver, would you mind turning...?
-Come back.


1857
01:54:19.329 --> 01:54:22.730
-How long is this going to take, Eugene?
-I didn't bring any medals.


1858
01:54:22.899 --> 01:54:24.389
Now what? I wanna get to bed.

1859
01:54:24.568 --> 01:54:28.595
You hear me? I said
I didn't have any--


1860
01:54:31.741 --> 01:54:33.436
Oh....

1861
01:54:33.610 --> 01:54:35.737
What are you staring at?

1862
01:54:35.912 --> 01:54:40.611
Vernon, old man, I
wonder if you'd give me...


1863
01:54:40.784 --> 01:54:42.081
...one of your medals?

1864
01:54:42.252 --> 01:54:43.549
What?

1865
01:54:43.720 --> 01:54:46.621
Just one, Vernon, please.

1866
01:54:46.790 --> 01:54:49.884
You've got so many of them.

1867
01:54:50.093 --> 01:54:54.154
-What are you talking about, Eugene?
-Stockdale wants a medal.


1868
01:54:54.664 --> 01:54:56.962
That does it. He
goes to Leavenworth.


1869
01:54:57.133 --> 01:54:59.966
No, no.

1870
01:55:00.136 --> 01:55:01.763
We might go with him.

1871
01:55:01.938 --> 01:55:06.432
Vernon, if you give me one of
yours, I'll give you two of mine.


1872
01:55:06.610 --> 01:55:09.875
-I swear I will.
-But these medals are sewn on.


1873
01:55:10.046 --> 01:55:11.604
BUSH: Sewn? POLLARD:
Yes, by heavens.


1874
01:55:11.781 --> 01:55:14.079
His medals are sewn on.

1875
01:55:14.251 --> 01:55:16.719
I got my mumblety-peg knife.

1876
01:55:18.321 --> 01:55:21.290
Just a small one,
please, Vernon?


1877
01:55:21.458 --> 01:55:24.950
I'll do this in private,
if you don't mind.


1878
01:55:25.762 --> 01:55:28.390
ANNOUNCER [OVER RADIO]:
This is radio station WQUID...


1879
01:55:28.565 --> 01:55:31.398
...now presenting a medley
of your favorite band music.


1880
01:55:31.568 --> 01:55:35.868
There's nothing else you can
think of at this moment, is there?


1881
01:55:36.039 --> 01:55:40.135
You do realize why we don't
have a brass band, don't you?


1882
01:55:40.944 --> 01:55:43.811
I wouldn't worry about that
none, sir. This here'll do fine.


1883
01:55:43.980 --> 01:55:46.175
I'll just get everybody
lined up over here.


1884
01:55:46.349 --> 01:55:48.112
[BAND MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO]

1885
01:55:48.685 --> 01:55:51.813
-Y'all come on in! KING:
Resist! On the double!


1886
01:55:51.988 --> 01:55:53.922
Everybody come on in!

1887
01:55:54.090 --> 01:55:55.682
KING: On the double.
SENTRY: Come on.


1888
01:55:55.859 --> 01:55:58.225
KING: Line up, boy,
right here. Come on.


1889
01:55:58.395 --> 01:56:01.421
Come on, give me the
papers. Line up on the double.


1890
01:56:07.504 --> 01:56:10.996
I've been blackmailed, I've been
shanghaied, I've been shot at...


1891
01:56:11.174 --> 01:56:12.971
...and now I've been robbed.

1892
01:56:13.143 --> 01:56:14.167
By dog.

1893
01:56:14.344 --> 01:56:17.802
Boy, Ben's gonna pop his shirt when
both of you generals snap to attention.


1894
01:56:17.981 --> 01:56:20.142
-Do what?
-Vernon, please.


1895
01:56:20.317 --> 01:56:21.944
Never.

1896
01:56:22.118 --> 01:56:23.676
BUSH: I'll stand at attention.

1897
01:56:23.853 --> 01:56:27.983
I'll stand on my head if
you'll just sign these papers.


1898
01:56:28.158 --> 01:56:29.182
I'll go fetch Ben.

1899
01:56:29.359 --> 01:56:31.122
-Have the orders to read?
-Yes, sir.


1900
01:56:31.294 --> 01:56:33.319
-Good.
-I'll get Ben.


1901
01:56:35.065 --> 01:56:36.089
Come on, Ben.

1902
01:56:36.266 --> 01:56:39.633
No, Will. Don't they give you
one last request or something?


1903
01:56:39.803 --> 01:56:42.863
BUSH: All right, you asked
for it. Come out and get it.


1904
01:56:43.039 --> 01:56:48.067
That's right, Ben. Now, strut
right up to the general and salute.


1905
01:56:48.545 --> 01:56:51.207
He's got something
he's gonna give you.


1906
01:56:51.481 --> 01:56:53.039
I know.

1907
01:56:53.416 --> 01:56:55.145
Goodbye, Will.

1908
01:57:05.595 --> 01:57:06.619
King.

1909
01:57:06.796 --> 01:57:09.594
"The following enlisted men
are hereby relieved of duty...


1910
01:57:09.766 --> 01:57:13.429
...and removed from the records
of Major General Eugene Bush...


1911
01:57:13.603 --> 01:57:16.834
...and transferred to the command
of Major General Vernon Pollard...


1912
01:57:17.007 --> 01:57:19.601
...U.S. Army infantry."

1913
01:57:19.776 --> 01:57:22.074
-What?
-Private Benjamin B. Whitledge.


1914
01:57:22.245 --> 01:57:26.511
-Private Will Stockdale.
-We're in the infantry, Ben.


1915
01:57:26.683 --> 01:57:28.014
-The infantry?
-Yeah.


1916
01:57:28.184 --> 01:57:29.742
Well, so long, boys.

1917
01:57:29.919 --> 01:57:31.853
It's been swell knowing you.

1918
01:57:32.022 --> 01:57:33.785
-So long, sergeant.
-So long, sergeant.


1919
01:57:33.957 --> 01:57:36.755
Wish I could be going
along with you, but that's life.


1920
01:57:38.461 --> 01:57:41.225
Hey, couldn't he, sir?
Couldn't he go along with us?


1921
01:57:41.398 --> 01:57:44.856
Brilliant idea,
Stockdale. Brilliant.


1922
01:57:45.035 --> 01:57:47.230
No, no, no.

1923
01:57:47.404 --> 01:57:50.999
-We are still gonna be together.
-In the infantry.


1924
01:57:51.174 --> 01:57:52.903
What happened?

1925
01:57:53.076 --> 01:57:55.237
Detail, attention.

1926
01:57:55.412 --> 01:57:58.711
That's one thing I won't do.

1927
01:57:59.349 --> 01:58:01.715
ANNOUNCER: Station
WQUID signing off.


1928
01:58:01.885 --> 01:58:04.786
[DRUMROLL OVER RADIO]

1929
01:58:06.856 --> 01:58:10.587
It gives me great pleasure
to award this Air Medal...


1930
01:58:10.760 --> 01:58:13.058
...which through a
regrettable error...


1931
01:58:13.229 --> 01:58:16.096
...was previously
awarded posthumously...


1932
01:58:16.266 --> 01:58:20.362
...to Private Benjamin
B. Whitledge...


1933
01:58:20.537 --> 01:58:24.029
...U.S. Army infantry.

1934
01:58:24.474 --> 01:58:26.374
MAN: Present arms.

1935
01:58:26.543 --> 01:58:28.534
["THE STAR-SPANGLED
BANNER" PLAYS OVER RADIO]


1936
01:58:55.105 --> 01:58:57.096
[ENGLISH SDH]